nt yet in the Trump-Russia affair. Prosecutors on Friday asked a federal judge to sentence former Trump campaign chairman <strong>Paul Manafort</strong> to a prison term between 20 and 24 years&#8212;plausibly a life sentence for the 69-year-old lobbyist.</p>\n<p>“Manafort acted for more than a decade as if he were above the law, and deprived the federal government and various financial institutions of millions of dollars,” prosecutors wrote in a court filing of Manafort’s <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/02/paul-manafort-could-really-use-that-pardon-right-about-now\">eight convictions on counts of financial fraud</a>. “The sentence here should reflect the seriousness of these crimes, and serve to both deter Manafort and others from engaging in such conduct . . . Manafort chose to do this for no other reason than greed, evidencing his belief that the law does not apply to him.”</p>\n<p>Manafort also pleaded guilty to two felony conspiracy charges as part of a cooperation agreement in September, but Mueller argued that plea deal was voided when Manafort allegedly misled prosecutors about his interactions with Russian business associate <strong>Konstantin Kilimnik,</strong> a former intelligence agent, as well as his contact with the Trump administration. Attorneys for Manafort argued at the time that their client’s mis-statements were unintentional, an assessment with which U.S. District Judge <strong>Amy Berman Jackson</strong> did not agree. Jackson concluded this past week that Manafort repeatedly lied during his plea agreement to assist investigators documenting Russia’s interference in the 2016 election.</p>\n<p>According to <em><a href=\"https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/02/15/paul-manafort-deserves-prison-sentence-20-years-mueller-says/2881393002/\">USA Today</a>,</em> prosecutors are also seeking that Manafort “be held liable for restitution and forfeited properties totaling up to nearly $30 million.” As to the punishment’s severity, prosecutors wrote, “Manafort’s age does not eliminate the risk of recidivism he poses&#8212;particularly given that his pattern of criminal activity has occurred over more than a decade. Manafort’s misconduct continued as recently as October 2018 when he repeatedly and intentionally lied to the government during proffer sessions and the grand jury.”</p>\n<p>President <strong>Donald Trump</strong> has not responded to news of the prosecution’s recommendation. He has previously floated the possibility of pardoning his former campaign chair, and <a href=\"https://twitter.com/realdonaldtrump/status/1032256443985084417\">claimed in an August tweet</a> that he felt “very badly” for Manafort and his family. “‘Justice’ took a 12 year old tax case, among other things, applied tremendous pressure on him and, unlike <strong>Michael Cohen,</strong> he refused to ‘break’ - make up stories in order to get a ‘deal.’ Such respect for a brave man!”</p>","rubric":"Locked Up","socialTitle":"Robert Mueller May Have Handed Paul Manafort a Life Sentence","socialDescription":"Manafort, convicted on eight counts of financial fraud in August, is facing upwards of 20 years behind bars.","seoTitle":"Robert Mueller May Have Handed Paul Manafort a Life Sentence","seoDescription":"Manafort, convicted on eight counts of financial fraud in August, is facing upwards of 20 years behind bars.","channel":"News","subChannel":"Politics","issueDate":"","ledeCaption":"","contentSource":"web","canonicalUrl":"","interactiveOverride":"","contentType":"","textMimeType":"","tags":["paul manafort","paul j. manafort","robert mueller"],"revisionAuthor":"Rachel Freeman","meta":{"collectionName":"articles","modelName":"article","publishable":true,"identifiable":true,"image":false,"archived":false,"hallable":true,"hierarchical":false},"id":"5c684065005f7f310e159614","revision":14,"createdAt":"February 16, 2019 11:55 am","modifiedAt":"February 19, 2019 8:44 am","revisionCreatedAt":"February 19, 2019 8:44 am","_e