999 Oscars ceremony, honoring the films of 1998, was a watershed one in several ways. It was the first to air on a Sunday night and the first to see the <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/12/shakespeare-in-love-and-harvey-weinsteins-dark-oscar-victory\">dark juggernaut of a Miramax Oscar campaign</a> fell a formidable opponent. With the Oscars of the present day in a state of disarray, let’s take a nostalgic look back at the way things were. (As we did for <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2013/02/1994-oscars-recap\">1994</a>, <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/02/1995-oscars-recap\">1995</a>, <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/02/1996-oscars-recap\">1996</a>, <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/02/1997-oscars-recap\">1997</a>, and <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/02/1998-oscars-recap\">1998</a>.)</em></p>\n<p>It’s Sunday at the Oscars! For the first time, actually. The show used to be on Mondays. In honor of that monumental shift, ABC aired a little pre-show special called <em>Sunday at the Oscars,</em> with your host, <strong>Geena Davis</strong>!</p>\n<p>Geena turns to the camera and says, “Oh, and there’s you, you nearly billion people, you.” A billion people!! Sigh, the old days. Geena asks those billion people,“How are you?” Then, “No, really. How are you?” Could audiences talk back to the TV and actually be heard 20 years ago? How did we lose that technology?</p>\n<p>Geena then says that she forgot to introduce her escort, “the guy everyone wants to go home with this evening.” A kind of dorky looking guy walks out and Geena’s like, “Uh uh.” She’s talking about Oscar, not you, dork!</p>\n<p>Then Geena takes a little break and cuts to an interview with one of the evening’s big nominees, <strong>Gwyneth Paltrow.</strong> She says being at the Oscars is “deeply thrilling and validating.”</p>\n<p>Next up is the soon-to-be chair-walker himself, <em>Life Is Beautiful</em> director, writer, and star <strong>Roberto Benigni.</strong> “Hello, Jeem!” he says to <em>Sunday at the Oscars</em> co-host <strong>Jim Moret.</strong></p>\n<p>It’s funny that for a whole awards season, everyone had to deal with a crazy Italian jumping bean and his Holocaust comedy.</p>\n<p>For some reason, while Benigni is talking, the camera cuts randomly to <strong>Goldie Hawn.</strong></p>\n<p>Then the poor presenter tries to segue to a new segment, but Benigni is having none of it. Poor Jeem has to stand there and give an “It’s a living” grimace.</p>\n<p>Finally Jeem gets to the next bit, which is a little thing about how the Oscar statuettes were made in Chicago and then taken on a multi-city whistle-stop tour on their way to Hollywood. There was a sheriff-type guy guarding them the whole time.</p>\n<p>Then it’s back where we belong, with Goldie Hawn. (And <strong>Steve Martin</strong> and <strong>Kurt Russell.</strong>) Goldie seems happy, like she has a little secret.</p>\n<p>We get a glimpse of some of the stars on the red carpet, including <strong>Drew Barrymore,</strong> fresh off of <em>The Wedding Singer</em> and <em>Ever After.</em></p>\n<p>Now it’s back to Geena, who has relocated to the “Countdown Center.”</p>\n<p>The Countdown Center seems like a pretty unremarkable room, until it’s revealed to contain . . . <strong>Helen Hunt</strong>!</p>\n<p>Helen’s looking great.</p>\n<p>Geena plays a clip of Helen winning best actress the previous year. Present-day Helen looks on with wonder.</p>\n<p>Helen talks to Geena about directing the series finale of <em>Mad About You,</em> as all acting-Oscar winners from 1992&#8211;1999 were required to direct an episode of that show. “It’s unlike anything anybody’s ever seen. We made a little movie,” Helen says of the episode. Is that accurate?</p>\n<p>Geena then has to go to the next segment, and Helen isn’t really sure what to do during the transition.</p>\n<p>It’s time for a little clip feature, voiced by Geena, about the history of Oscars fashion. The reel features <strong>Barbra Streisand</strong> in a famous wacky number.</p>\n<p>There’s <strong>Jada Pinkett Smith,</strong> doing an alluring red carpet dance.</p>\n<p>And then! Our first (and sadly last) glimpse of Oscars Kween <strong>Sharon Stone</strong>!!!</p>\n<p>Watching this pre-show, I got very confused about why Geena Davis was doing it. Was it all just to promote the upcoming <em>Stuart Little</em>? Did she see <em>The Geena Davis Show</em> glimmering on the horizon? Was this part of some <em>Cutthroat Island</em>-related community-service sentence? We may never know.</p>\n<p>Doing these “Oscars 20 years” recaps is fun, but it’s also a little melancholy, looking back at a not-so-distant past and realizing how many things occurred that would never again. I don’t even recognize some of the names and faces! Like, who is this person who was apparently nominated for an Oscar that year??</p>\n<p>But seriously, remember when we were nominating <strong>Emily Watson</strong> for Oscars? We should start doing that again.</p>\n<p>Elsewhere on the carpet, there’s <strong>Tom Hanks,</strong> sporting what I’m assuming is some stage of his <em>Cast Away</em> beard.</p>\n<p>Then it’s back to the Countdown Center, where Geena is talking to <em>Affliction</em> supporting-actor nominee James Coburn. It slowly becomes clear that Geena Davis has not seen <em>Affliction.</em></p>\n<p>Then there’s a somewhat extended sequence in which Geena turns her back to us and talks at a screen. It’s really dynamic television.</p>\n<p><strong>Liv Tyler,</strong> at perhaps the height of her fame, post-<em>Armageddon,</em> attended the Oscars for the first time.</p>\n<p>Now it’s time for a little recap of the nominations process and the nominees luncheon!</p>\n<p>Oh dear.</p>\n<p>Ohhhhhh dear.</p>\n<p>Well, at least <strong>Warren Beatty,</strong> nominated for his <em>Bulworth</em> screenplay, was having an unimpeachable good time.</p>\n<p>And look! It’s baby <strong>Cate Blanchett</strong>! (This was her first nomination, for playing Elizabeth in <em>Elizabeth.</em>)</p>\n<p>After a bit about the set and rehearsal process for the big show, Geena Davis is joined in her room of requirement by a fabulously chapeau’d <strong>Céline Dion.</strong></p>\n<p>Céline immediately starts laughing.</p>\n<p>Geena Davis asks Céline about her rumored retirement. Céline says, “I want to try to have a little baby.” Which, sadly, never came true. As we all know, Céline Dion’s baby was enormous.</p>\n<p>Time for more red carpet shots! There’s <strong>Liam Neeson</strong> giving us the thumbs-up.</p>\n<p>And his <em>Cold Pursuit</em> co-star, <strong>Laura Dern.</strong></p>\n<p>There are some ads on this recording of the show. Including . . . <strong>Melanie Griffith</strong>!</p>\n<p>Also, an ad for the pants of the day.</p>\n<p>Jeem takes us on a tour of the Governors Ball, which apparently was held on the leftover Poison Ivy sets from <em>Batman &amp; Robin.</em></p>\n<p>And that’s that for this curiously low-key pre-show. Geena grabs her Oscar and trudges out of the Countdown Center. Of course, we know that she never actually left that room&#8212;that she’s said to still roam it, counting down forever. But we didn’t know that then. Then, we were only excited, because the show was about to begin!</p>\n<p>Now, only 48 screenshots in, it’s time for the main event.</p>\n<p>Cate Blanchett is thrilled about that!</p>\n<p>Hey look! Helen Hunt made it out of the walls of the Countdown Center and would like to say hello.</p>\n<p>Now that we’re inside, it’s time for host <strong>Whoopi Goldberg</strong> to make her famous entrance, dressed as Queen Elizabeth and searing herself into the brains of children the world over. These three blonde women approve.</p>\n<p>Cate liked it, because of <em>Elizabeth.</em></p>\n<p>Gwyneth liked it, because of <em>Shakespeare in Love.</em></p>\n<p>And <strong>Uma Thurman</strong> liked it for some reason too?</p>\n<p><strong>Ed Harris</strong> seems a bit confused.</p>\n<p>Whoopi introduces herself as “the African queen,” which gets a hearty laugh. In character, she jokes about how many movies that year involved Queen Elizabeth&#8212;I believe it was two&#8212;and then cracks wise about the length of the Oscars broadcast. “This will be a long show, so we don’t want to read about how damn long it was. We know it’s long. Tough.” Ohh, those were the days, weren’t they? When the Academy wasn’t <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/02/can-the-2019-oscars-be-saved\">madly scrambling to trim the show everywhere it can</a>, instead just leaning into the luxurious length of a Sunday at the Oscars?</p>\n<p><strong>Renée Zellweger</strong> agrees.</p>\n<p>Whoopi continues on with the show-length bit <em>and</em> the queen bit by saying, “I think we’ve all had our hair done enough times to know that you cannot rush a queen.” Oh! It’s a gay joke!</p>\n<p>Goldie and Kurt are not sure how to react to that one.</p>\n<p>Then there’s a tired <strong>Elton John</strong> joke (this dress really belongs to him!) and then Whoopi has to leave to get out of that crazy costume. So, she gives the stage over to then-Academy president <strong>Robert Rehme,</strong> joking that he was the guy who put Ned Devine to sleep. (<em>Waking Ned Devine</em> was big that year.)</p>\n<p>Goldie liked that one!</p>\n<p>When Rehme takes the stage, he seems less than pleased with the joke.</p>\n<p>Whoopi wasn’t wrong, and Rehme is totally boring. He introduces the evening’s first montage, a salute to movie scenes that the Academy likes. That’s all! Nothing more specific than that. Then it’s time for the Whoopster to really do her thing, but first we get a full glimpse of the strange bat-wing set they designed for the show that year.</p>\n<p>“This is the biggest party in Hollywood,” Whoopi says of the Oscars. “Well, maybe second biggest if you count the Democrats.” Hollywood liberalism in action! “This is the last Oscars show before the millennium,” she continues. Which is weird to think about. Not that it was the last Oscars show before the millennium, but that we were all so obsessed with the new millennium back then. What a big deal it was! Now we’re 19 rotten years in, and what has this millennium got to show for itself? Not a whole heck of a lot.</p>\n<p>But anyway, Whoopi makes a funny joke calling herself “the last 20th-century fox.” Goldie’s into it!</p>\n<p>Whoopi then does a “We Didn’t Start the Fire”&#8211;esque spoken-word list of terms related to Lewinskygate. It’s pretty corny, as are the next few bits in Whoopi’s speech, including a “Much Nothing About a ’Do” joke connecting Shakespeare and <em>There’s Something About Mary.</em> Gwyneth tries to laugh sincerely, but Whoopi knows she’s failed.</p>\n<p>Then there’s a bit about how the Oscar campaigns were so out of hand that year, particularly between Miramax (which had <em>Shakespeare in Love</em>) and DreamWorks (which had <em>Saving Private Ryan</em>). Whoopi says, “Those boys fought World War III over World War II!” The DreamWorks wives try to play it cool.</p>\n<p>Then it’s time to get specific about the nominees. Gwyneth Paltrow’s role in <em>Shakespeare in Love,</em> a woman pretending to be a man so she can be in a play, marks “the only time in history that a woman had her breasts reduced to get a part.” Gwyneth is tickled.</p>\n<p>Whoopi makes another queen joke, saying that <strong>Judi Dench</strong> is bound to play every queen in England. “Next year, she’s doing Boy George!” Quite a gag.</p>\n<p>That’s pretty much it for the lackluster opening monologue. It’s time to hand out the first award! To introduce presenter <strong>Kim Basinger,</strong> Whoopi says, “Last year, she took home two of the best-looking men in Hollywood: Oscar and <strong>Alec Baldwin.</strong>” Only 20 years ago, people were making jokes about how hot Alec Baldwin was. Just 20 short years.</p>\n<p>James Coburn wins for <em>Affliction,</em> and the lady behind him is very excited.</p>\n<p>During a commercial break, we catch a glimpse of this girl. Remember her?? From the ads??</p>\n<p>Now it’s time for Gwyneth Paltrow to present best art direction. “She actually did Shakespeare,” Whoopi jokes. “Please welcome best-actress nominee and sweet kid, Gwyneth Paltrow.”</p>\n<p>It’s kind of crazy how much of a coronation this whole night was for Gwyneth Paltrow. Look at that walk! It’s like she’s about to marry a prince in a Christmas movie.</p>\n<p>What good fortune that her film, <em>Shakespeare in Love,</em> wins the category. It’s the film’s first victory over heavy favorite <em>Saving Private Ryan.</em> It will not be the last. After that, <strong>Patrick Stewart</strong> comes out to introduce the first two best-picture nominees, <em>Shakespeare in Love</em> and <em>Elizabeth.</em></p>\n<p>While introducing the next presenter, Whoopi jokes that she’s always entering from stage left because of a “vast right-wing conspiracy.” How many more Lewinsky jokes will there be tonight?</p>\n<p><strong>Mike Myers</strong> shows up to promote <em>The Spy Who Shagged Me</em> and present best makeup. He makes a Zsa Zsa Gabor/mascara joke that <strong>Meryl Streep</strong> (nominated for <em>One True Thing</em>) just adores!</p>\n<p><em>Elizabeth</em> wins the makeup prize, and Cate Blanchett is profusely thanked. She takes it all modestly.</p>\n<p>And she gives a heartfelt round of applause.</p>\n<p>At long last, something big is about to happen! <strong>Christina Ricci</strong> comes out to introduce the first best-song nominee, a real barn-burner&#8212;or, I mean, bush-burner&#8212;called “When You Believe,” from the underrated animated film <em>The Prince of Egypt.</em> Ricci’s dress strap keeps falling down, as was the style at the time.</p>\n<p>It’s a big, righteous number&#8212;how could it not be, with <strong>Mariah Carey</strong> and Whitney Houstondebbie duetting?</p>\n<p>I’m a little confused about this triangle of gospel singers, but I’ll take a surprise gospel-choir reveal in any form. I’m glad those haven’t gone out of fashion.</p>\n<p>Then Whoopi comes out in a <em>Pleasantville</em> get-up and makes a <strong>Marilyn Quayle</strong> joke.</p>\n<p>I got excited that this recording is evidently from Boston, meaning whoever recorded this thing I’m watching in 2019 was sitting somewhere in my general vicinity when we both watched the Oscars that night, 20 years ago. Man. Time! Time.</p>\n<p>Anyhoo, Whoopi makes a beaver joke&#8212;having vaguely to do with <em>Leave It to Beaver</em>&#8212;and she makes a wicked little stinker face.</p>\n<p><strong>Nick Nolte,</strong> a nominee that night, loved it!</p>\n<p>So did Warren Beatty.</p>\n<p>Then it’s time for <strong>Brendan Fraser.</strong> He’d have a big hit in a couple months with <em>The Mummy.</em> But for now, he’s focused on little things: the live-action shorts!</p>\n<p>First he does a PowerPoint presentation about culture.</p>\n<p><em>Valgaften</em> wins! I’ll never forget the excitement of <em>Valgaften</em> winning. One of the directors loves a shoulder pad.</p>\n<p>Then a random lady comes out holding an Oscar. But for whom?</p>\n<p>She places the Oscar on the floor.</p>\n<p>Then the microphone lowers and lowers and lowers . . .</p>\n<p>. . . and then it’s the bug from <em>A Bug’s Life</em>!</p>\n<p>The bug is there to present best animated short, naturally. The announcer notes that the winning director worked on <em>Joe’s Apartment.</em> Surely the only time <em>Joe’s Apartment</em> has ever been mentioned at the Oscars?</p>\n<p>Then it’s time for best supporting actress, meaning Robin Williams takes the stage. He does a bowing bit that Roberto Benigni just loves.</p>\n<p>Robin makes some Robin-y jokes, topical silly stuff that is greeted with warm laughter. When Robin reads out the nominees, Judi Dench looks almost annoyed to hear her name.</p>\n<p>Is it possible that <strong>Blake Lively</strong> is older than we think and was seated behind Lynn Redgrave at the 1999 Oscars ceremony?</p>\n<p>Judi Dench is so mad when she wins.</p>\n<p>She cheers up by the end, though!</p>\n<p>After a commercial break, Whoopi gazes at a particular point in the audience and smirks. “Look at Goldie Hawn walking around!” she says. Goldie and Kurt aren’t back in their seats, so, they get called out, <em>Blue Man Group</em>&#8211;style.</p>\n<p>Goldie is forced to scoot past seat-holders, whom Whoopi has shooed from their chairs. Calamity!</p>\n<p>After that whole mess is settled, Whoopi goes riffing for a bit, eventually asking Roberto Benigni if he understands any of her jokes. He absolutely does not!</p>\n<p><strong>Chris Rock</strong> comes out to present sound-effects editing. “Thank you, <strong>Oprah,</strong>” he says to Whoopi. “It’s like the million white man march here!” He also mentions the Kazan thing&#8212;director Elia Kazan was receiving an honorary Oscar that night, amid much controversy&#8212;and gets some boos from the audience. Anyway, <em>Saving Private Ryan</em> wins its first award of the evening, on its way to an inevitable best-picture win. Right??</p>\n<p>It’s then Liv Tyler’s turn to introduce her dad and the rest of Aerosmith singing “I Don’t Want to Miss a Thing” from <em>Armageddon</em>&#8212;written by the great <strong>Diane Warren.</strong></p>\n<p>They do their usual Aerosmith thing and then there’s an older-man salute at the end. An older man in the audience responds.</p>\n<p><strong>Anjelica Huston</strong> then takes the stage to present best sound. Which is different than sound effects. This is before they changed the categories to sound mixing and sound editing. I like the blunt simplicity of “best sound.”</p>\n<p><em>Saving Private Ryan</em> wins, duh. Then it’s time for that film’s star, Tom Hanks, to do his Hanksian duty by waxing mistily about something Good and American. This time it’s astronaut John Glenn, who was having a moment because he went back to space as an old guy.</p>\n<p>Sure, sure, John Glenn was interesting, but OMG look at teen <strong>Mamie Gummer</strong>! Also, what’s Streep thinkin’ about, I wonder?</p>\n<p>Then it’s time for the “In Memoriam” segment. Incredible how many big names we lost in 1998.</p>\n<p>I could have sworn that Kennedy died in the 60s. No, I’m just joshing. Those names were just part of some sort of salute to real people who’ve been played on-screen. Great men, and a few women, plus a genocidal maniac and a Nazi.</p>\n<p>Next, Whoopi comes out dressed like Oprah in <em>Beloved.</em> “I’m a slave to fashion,” she says, which doesn’t land all that well.</p>\n<p>After that, <strong>Sophia Loren</strong> takes the stage to introduce <em>Life Is Beautiful</em> as a best-picture nominee. Benigni is very excited to see his countrywoman there, and to be recognized by her.</p>\n<p>Then Loren gives out best foreign-language film to <em>Life Is Beautiful</em> and Benigni does his famous chair walk.</p>\n<p>He really milks this thing, taking a big bow on stage and giving Loren a long hug.</p>\n<p>Goldie loves it.</p>\n<p>Benigni declares his love for everyone, and everyone falls in love with him. (More, anyway.) He’ll be back on stage later in the evening, of course.</p>\n<p>Now it’s time for <strong>Andie MacDowell</strong> and <strong>Andy García</strong> to present best comedy score together, because it’s important to pair Andies when you can. This segment affords us the thrilling opportunity to hear Andie MacDowell say “Patch Adams.” What a treat. <em>Shakespeare in Love</em> wins, deservedly.</p>\n<p>Then Geena Davis reappears to present best dramatic score. Geena! Good to see you again!</p>\n<p>The really exciting thing about this is that there are <strong>Debbie Allen</strong>-choreographed dance numbers to accompany the nominees. It’s a whollllle thing.</p>\n<p>Like, really a whole thing.</p>\n<p><em>Life Is Beautiful</em> wins, because people really liked <em>Life Is Beautiful</em>!</p>\n<p>Then <strong>John Travolta</strong> comes out to introduce a tribute to Frank Sinatra, who died in May of 1998. Travolta doesn’t call him “Stank Elantra” or anything, so let’s just move on.</p>\n<p>Then, this.</p>\n<p>And then just the energy boost this show needs: It’s <strong>Anne Heche,</strong> here to tell us about her time at the technical awards, held earlier.</p>\n<p>Ironically, or maybe it’s a whole bit I’m just not getting, Heche has technical difficulties with her mic.</p>\n<p>But no worries. Heche is a pro, and sidles over to a podium with a working mic like she’s been possessed by awards queen Sharon Stone.</p>\n<p>After Anne leaves us, sadly, <strong>Jim Carrey</strong> walks on to present best editing. He makes a joke about how he wasn’t nominated for best actor for <em>The Truman Show,</em> which really was a snub.</p>\n<p>He pretends to cry and it’s pretty funny. <strong>Kate Capshaw</strong> is fuckin’ loving it.</p>\n<p>But, Carrey inevitably carries the bit on too long. He makes a Benigni joke that sounds just a <em>little</em> bitter, in a genuine sense. Oh well!</p>\n<p><em>Saving Private Ryan</em> wins, further indicating that the movie is going all the way. I think it will! What could possibly get in its way??</p>\n<p>Next up is Renée Zellweger introducing the nominated song from <em>The Horse Whisperer,</em> <strong>Robert Redford’s</strong> “Baby, You’re a Horse and I’m Gonna Whisper to Ya,” with backup vocals from a young <strong>Scarlett Johansson</strong> doing a <strong>Tom Waits</strong> impression. No! That’s a joke. The song is by <strong>Allison Moorer,</strong> and is the only nomination that underrated movie got. I know people say it’s a corny movie, but give it a watch. There’s a lot of beautiful stuff in there, not the least of which is <strong>Kristin Scott Thomas’s</strong> excellent performance as an <strong>Anna Wintour</strong> type going West.</p>\n<p>Anyway! After that nice little song is done, Whoopi comes out in a big feather dress and makes a joke about the movie <em>The Birds.</em> It’s a perfectly fine gag, but it’s crucially important in that it offers us a reaction shot of someone we haven’t seen yet tonight.</p>\n<p>Shot . . .</p>\n<p>Chaser!</p>\n<p>Jack! Of course he’s here to hand out best actress, but we hadn’t gotten any audience shots of him until now. Thanks, bird dress!</p>\n<p><strong>Nicolas Cage</strong> then takes the stage to introduce the Thalberg Award for his <em>Moonstruck</em> director, <strong>Norman Jewison.</strong></p>\n<p>We come back from commercial break and Whoopi calls Benigni “an insane Italian.” Whoopi then summons Liam Neeson to the stage, to present best visual effects. <em>Mighty Joe Young</em> was nominated! Remember <em>Mighty Joe Young</em>?</p>\n<p>The surprise here is that <em>What Dreams May Come</em> wins, beating out <em>Armageddon</em>’s riot of fire. So, <em>What Dreams May Come</em> officially has more Oscars than <strong>Annette Bening.</strong></p>\n<p>After that, well . . . I don’t know how else to say this, but <strong>Val Kilmer</strong> walks on stage wearing a cowboy hat and leading a horse. The horse is not very well-behaved.</p>\n<p>Kilmer and the horse are there to pay tribute to screen cowboys Roy Rogers and Gene Autry, who died the previous summer. The horse is still not having it.</p>\n<p>Next up is Helen Hunt to present best actor. She gesticulates very passionately, as if she knows who’s about to win.</p>\n<p>Benigni wins, of course, becoming the first performer to win a lead-acting Oscar for a foreign-language film since Sophia Loren. It’s funny that Helen Hunt and Roberto Benigni have kissed on the cheek.</p>\n<p>He charmingly jokes that he’s used up all his English. But he does manage to say, “My body is in toomoolt,” and that he wants to make love to everybody, like Jupiter. I kinda feel like Helen Hunt is considering it.</p>\n<p>After all that effusion, we take a commercial break. Upon return, it’s time for Whoopi to lip sync for her life. Or, at least, to show off one of the costumes from <em>Velvet Goldmine.</em></p>\n<p>People thought that <strong>Lisa Kudrow</strong> could maybe get a supporting-actress nomination for <em>The Opposite of Sex</em> in 1998. Instead, she got to present the <strong>Randy Newman</strong> song from <em>Babe: Pig in the City.</em></p>\n<p>It’s fun to think that Sophia Loren once sat and listened to a song from <em>Babe: Pig in the City.</em></p>\n<p>After that’s done, we hear, “Welcome last year’s versatile Academy Award winners <strong>Matt Damon</strong> and <strong>Ben Affleck.</strong>” Hm.</p>\n<p>They give out best documentary short subject, to a woman who used to be Miss Japan. Sadly, <strong>Keiko Ibi</strong> seems to have never made another movie? Sigh.</p>\n<p>Then it’s on to documentary feature, which goes to <em>The Last Days,</em> a Holocaust movie produced by <strong>Steven Spielberg.</strong></p>\n<p>Uh oh!!!! Now it’s time to give Elia Kazan his honorary Oscar. <strong>Martin Scorsese</strong> and <strong>Robert De Niro</strong> are on presenting duty. De Niro is hairstyled like a <em>Butt</em> magazine editorial intern because, I believe, he was filming <em>The Adventures of Rocky &amp; Bullwinkle</em> at the time. What a reason to look bizarre at the Oscars.</p>\n<p>There’s a whole stilted intro and then a clip reel and than Kazan comes out. If I remember anything from this Oscars it’s <strong>Ed Harris</strong> and <strong>Amy Madigan</strong> not only not standing, but not even clapping. They were some of the people upset that Kazan was winning the award despite the fact that he named names to Joe McCarthy during the whole H.U.A.C. thing.</p>\n<p>Nick Nolte got in on the action too.</p>\n<p>After that tense moment, Whoopi comes out in the last nominated costume. For <em>Shakespeare in Love</em>!</p>\n<p>Whoopi makes a joke about all her costume changes, saying she hasn’t had to take her dress off this many times since her first audition. “Steven, you remember . . .” she says to her <em>Color Purple</em> director Steven Spielberg.</p>\n<p><strong>Sandy Powell</strong> was nominated twice in 1998, for <em>Shakespeare in Love</em> and <em>Velvet Goldmine.</em> She wins for <em>Shakespeare.</em> This was her first win. She’s won two times since, for <em>The Aviator</em> and <em>The Young Victoria.</em> She’s up this year for both <em>Mary Poppins Returns</em> and <em>The Favourite.</em></p>\n<p>Then <strong>Catherine Zeta-Jones,</strong> hot off <em>The Mask of Zorro,</em> walks out to introduce the final nominated song.</p>\n<p>The song is “The Prayer,” from <em>Quest for Camelot,</em> a Warner Bros. attempt at a Disney-princess movie that was a total bomb. It got an Oscar nomination for its song, at least, here performed by Céline Dion and <strong>Andrea Bocelli.</strong> Predictably, they sing the hell out of it.</p>\n<p>Meryl Streep seems super into it.</p>\n<p>Then “an actress of depth and beauty,” <strong>Jennifer Lopez,</strong> presents the winner of best original song. Is she flirting with me?</p>\n<p>“When You Believe” wins. <strong>Stephen Schwartz</strong> is not there to accept the trophy because he’s in New York rehearsing a show. Whitney seems displeased.</p>\n<p>Then it’s time for the actual “In Memoriam” segment. Here are some of the notable names.</p>\n<p>Folks, we’re almost there, I promise. For some reason, <strong>Colin Powell</strong> is introduced by former M.P.A.A. head Jack Valenti. He’s there to talk about <em>Saving Private Ryan</em> and <em>The Thin Red Line,</em> two World War II movies nominated for best picture.</p>\n<p>Once that’s over, Whoopi acknowledges the death of someone who wasn’t included in the “In Memoriam” reel: critic Gene Siskel. She gives a thumbs up to the heavens.</p>\n<p>It’s Uma Thurman’s turn to present, for best cinematography. She’s doing a weird British-ish accent? I guess a lot of people were doing that in the late 90s.</p>\n<p>Of course, the great <strong>Janusz Kamiński</strong> wins for <em>Saving Private Ryan,</em> pretty fitting considering he effectively <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/25-best-movie-scenes?verso=true\">changed the look of war movies forever</a>. A good win!</p>\n<p>Now it’s Jack time, baby. He looks happy as ever to be there, to present best actress.</p>\n<p>“I’m saying nothing because you’ve all exhausted every expression you have” is a great way to begin an award presentation toward the end of a long show. Classic Jack.</p>\n<p>Naturally it’s Gwyneth Paltrow who wins, her first and last nomination. (To date!) The waterworks start right away.</p>\n<p>She gets hugs from Blythe and Bruce and then heads to the stage.</p>\n<p>Gwyneth says, “My friend Cate Blanchett,” which is interesting. She also thanks, “The greatest one there ever was, Meryl Streep. I don’t feel very deserving in your presence.” Meryl appreciates that.</p>\n<p>Paltrow really loses it while thanking her family. It’s all very sweet.</p>\n<p>Blythe is having trouble handling it.</p>\n<p>A memorably emotional speech. Come back to acting, Gwyneth!</p>\n<p>Ugh. There’s more?? Yes, there is more. Just a little bit more. Stanley Kubrick had just died two weeks before the ceremony, so Steven Spielberg comes out to talk about that. Then it’s time for the screenplay awards. Steve Martin and Goldie Hawn are presenting.</p>\n<p>Steve asks Goldie if winning an Oscar was one of the most exciting moments of her life. She says, “Actually having my children was more exciting.” He responds, “Oh please,” and Goldie laughs gaily.</p>\n<p><em>Shakespeare in Love</em> and <em>Gods and Monsters</em> win the screenplay trophies, because the Academy likes stuff about showbiz.</p>\n<p>We’ve arrived at best director, which <strong>Kevin Costner</strong>&#8212;a winner for <em>Dances with Wolves</em>&#8212;is presenting.</p>\n<p>Spielberg wins, and gives Tom Hanks a lil’ kiss on the head.</p>\n<p>Ahh!! It’s her again!! And she’s talking like a mobster!</p>\n<p><strong>Harrison Ford</strong> emerges to put us out of our misery.</p>\n<p>And then the unthinkable happens: <em>Shakespeare in Love</em> wins.</p>\n<p>Yikes.</p>\n<p>Me neither, girl.</p>\n<p>Look, <em>Shakespeare in Love</em> is a wonderful movie, but obviously it’s been tainted some by the big man who muscled its way to this Oscar win. Still, I suppose we can focus on the many positives of the movie and not its clear negatives.</p>\n<p>Anyway, let’s skip <strong>Harvey Weinstein’s</strong> acceptance speech and move on to the end. Because we’re there! We’ve finished!</p>\n<p>Whoopi comes out for one last blessing, thanking the audience watching at home and nicely calling back to Keiko Ibi as an inspiration to follow your dreams.</p>\n<p>And that’s it, folks. See you next year!</p>\n<p>Toodles!</p>","rubric":"Nostalgia","socialTitle":"Recapping the 1999 Oscars Ceremony, When Shakespeare Beat Spielberg","socialDescription":"It was Saving Private Ryan versus Shakespeare in Love at the dawn of the modern Oscar campaign.","seoTitle":"From 2019 to 1999: Recapping the Oscars 20 Years Ago","seoDescription":"It was Saving Private Ryan versus Shakespeare in Love at the dawn of the modern Oscar campaign.","channel":"Hollywood","subChannel":"Award Season","issueDate":"","ledeCaption":"","contentSource":"web","canonicalUrl":"","interactiveOverride":"","contentType":"","textMimeType":"","tags":["movies"],"revisionAuthor":"Brad Beatson","meta":{"collectionName":"articles","modelName":"article","publishable":true,"identifiable":true,"image":false,"archived":false,"hallable":true,"hierarchical":false},"id":"5c6b97de3fc1123162a5c983","revision":68,"createdAt":"February 19, 2019 12:45 am","modifiedAt":"February 19, 2019 4:56 pm","revisionCreatedAt":"February 19, 2019 4:56 pm","_embedded":{"categories-channels":[{"fields":{"name":"Award Season","slug":"award-season","revi