cumentary</a> about her life that is showing at the <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/sundance-2019-preview-14-films-to-watch\">Sundance Film Festival</a>, and she’s not going to rest until she gets one. The 90-year-old has lived a multitude of lives, from German-Jewish World War II refugee and orphan, to radio sex therapist, to television talk show host. She toured through the snowy streets of the Sundance Film Festival this weekend to talk about <em>Ask Dr. Ruth,</em> the Hulu doc directed by <em>The Keepers</em> filmmaker <strong>Ryan White,</strong> and advocated all the while for the film’s place at the 2020 Academy Awards.</p>\n<p>“The film needs an Oscar nomination,” she said with her unmistakably giggly laugh. “Just the nomination. If something else comes along, too, like the prize, you can have it,” she said, motioning to White.</p>\n<p>It’s not a crazy proposition. The doc, which White shot over the better part of the last two years, tracks Westheimer’s traumatic childhood when, at age 10, she was sent to an orphanage in Switzerland as part of the <a href=\"https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/kindertransport-1938-40\">Kindertransport</a> at the beginning of WWII. (It was the last time she ever saw her parents.) From there, the film travels to Israel, where Westheimer lived on a kibbutz and had her sexual awakening, then to Paris with her first husband, where she began studying for a college degree (she eventually received a doctorate in education from Columbia University’s Teachers College). The film then tracks her arrival in New York, where, as a single mother who divorced her second husband, she found her calling with sex therapy, married her longtime partner, Fred Westheimer, and rose to fame as the woman who spoke the truth about sex and advocated for gay rights.</p>\n<p>Filmmakers have been trying to make a documentary about Westheimer’s life for decades. She says she’s received offers from all over the world. Now was the first time when she felt the need to tell her story.</p>\n<p>“There is an obligation by me to stand up and be counted for some of the things that are happening today,” she said. “Even though I don’t do politics, I’m very upset about what’s happening with <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/10/donald-trump-child-detention-crisis-is-getting-worse\">children being separated from their parents</a>, because that’s my story. But I also said yes because I need to combat the people that are deniers of the Holocaust, and who have fatigue [from hearing about the] Holocaust, to make sure something like this doesn’t happen again.”</p>\n<div class=\"embed cneembed\"><div class=\"embed block cneembed\" data-url=\"//player.cnevids.com/script/video/5c4fbec8279551454b000012.js?muted=1\"></div></div><p>A very poignant moment in the film follows Westheimer to <a href=\"https://www.yadvashem.org/\">Yad Vashem</a>, the World Holocaust Remembrance Center in Jerusalem, where visitors can look up the names of the people who perished during Germany’s Nazi regime. Westheimer knew her parents had died at the hand of the Nazis prior to visiting the museum, but wanted others to know that the institution and its database exists.</p>\n<p>“I wanted to be able to teach young people that the older generation had horrible things happen to them, and that the Nazis kept track of each single person, with their birth date and their death date,” Westheimer said. “I knew already that next to my mother’s name it says the German word for ‘disappear.’ It makes me very sad. All I can think about is, disappear where? Where is her grave? One important part of what has happened here [with this documentary] is now, symbolically, I have a grave for my whole family.”</p>\n<p>It’s easy to fall in love with Westheimer. Her joyous spirit and easy laugh are contagious&#8212;and that’s before you ask her any sex questions. Being in her 90s has not curbed any of her enthusiasm.</p>\n<p>And she can’t stop raving about White’s work on the film&#8212;hence the quest for an Academy Award&#8212;from his ability to balance the light and the dark in her life, to the film’s animated segments, which beautifully illustrate her time in the orphanage, and initially concerned her. “I was worried,” Westheimer said. “I didn’t want it turned into a cartoon.”</p>\n<p>White was similarly concerned.</p>\n<p>“It was a huge boon that Dr. Ruth had kept all those letters from her parents&#8212;what amazing content for a documentary filmmaker, to be able to use her voice and her parents’ voices. But how do you illustrate it?” asked White. “I always wanted her childhood to be a big part of the film, but I didn’t want to use B-roll of train stations and footage from the Holocaust to tell these harrowing tales. I was obsessed with [her] eyes, and making sure the animated version of [her] eyes looked just like the real ones, since I wanted all the animation to be seen through [them].”</p>\n<p>Westheimer is specifically charged by the poignancy of the animated sequence inside a Frankfurt train station when she says goodbye to her mother and grandmother as she departs to Switzerland, waving to them from inside the train while the two women clutch each other on a platform.</p>\n<p>“That railroad station was filled with people, but for me, the only thing that counted were my mother and grandmother, standing there,” Westheimer said. “That station was filled with loneliness. It just cries out to you. I’ve never seen in my life the graphic version of loneliness. It’s brilliant. And it’s absolutely true.”</p>\n<p>It’s also something Westheimer wants to use in her family-and-media class at Teachers College. Yes, she still teaches. She’s also currently working on a new version of her 1995 best-selling book, <em>Sex For Dummies,</em> this time focused on millennials. She’s worried about what modern technology is doing to our culture, concerned specifically with issues of loneliness and how smartphones usurp our ability to communicate with each other.</p>\n<p>“If it’s two people going on a date, that phone is always on the table as if there is something happening in the world they have to know about right now,” Westheimer said. “People are going to lose the art of conversation. You see families at a restaurant and the kids are on the phone and the adults are on the phone. It’s just a catastrophe.”</p>\n<p>Westheimer’s life and outlook is reminder of the indelible human spirit. So what say you, Academy? Time for an Oscar?</p>\n<h3>More Great Stories from <em>Vanity Fair</em></h3>\n<p>&#8212; <em>Bohemian Rhapsody</em>’s long and troubled <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/bohemian-rhapsody-oscar-nominations?inline\">road to the Oscars</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; A defense of <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2019/01/nell-scovell-lean-in?inline\">leaning in</a>, by the co-author of Lean In</p>\n<p>&#8212; The <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/judd-apatow-louis-ck-kevin-hart-crashing-comedy-interview?inline\">Judd Apatow theory of comedy</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; A visual <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2019/01/amalia-andrade-book-interview?inline\">guide to heartbreak that will make you laugh</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; A long-overdue win for <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/2019-oscar-nominations-overdue-for-black-filmmakers?inline\">black filmmakers</a></p>\n<p>Looking for more? <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/newsletters\">Sign up</a> for our daily Hollywood newsletter and never miss a story.</p>","rubric":"Sundance Film Festival","socialTitle":"Dr. Ruth Westheimer Thinks Her Sundance Doc Ask Dr. Ruth is Oscar-Worthy","socialDescription":"She wants a 2020 Academy Award nomination, and she’s not afraid to say it at Sundance a year out.","seoTitle":"Sundance Doc Ask Dr. Ruth Should Get a 2020 Oscar Nomination According to Dr. Ruth Westheimer","seoDescription":"Dr. Ruth Westheimer wants a 2020 Academy 