ore moving to the streaming platform, <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/netflix-you-bird-box-viewers-numbers\">was on track to be “watched by over 40 million member households”</a> in its first four weeks on its new platform&#8212;but Landgraf took issue with that number, saying that the streamer had counted households watching just part of an episode, rather than only considering total viewership per episode. If you applied standard metrics to their data, he claimed, it would look more like eight million viewers per episode&#8212;a respectable number, but not the enormous phenomenon Netflix has reported the show to be.</p>\n<p>“By reporting their singles as if they were home runs,” Landgraf said, the streamer has misrepresented both the number and the true scale of its hits&#8212;suggesting that it alone has figured out the secret to the TV universe.</p>\n<p>“The truth will ultimately come out, as it always does,” he quipped.</p>\n<p>In December, FX released a <a href=\"https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-peak-tv-fx-2018-report-20181213-story.html\">report</a> suggesting that for the first time, streamers are churning out more original content than broadcast and cable networks: 160 scripted original series ran on streaming services last year (not counting reality shows or kids programs), compared to 146 on broadcast networks and 144 on basic cable. During this panel, Landgraf also noted that FX is “laser-focused” on quality rather than quantity. He pointed out that FX (which expects to become part of Disney following Disney’s acquisition of major Fox assets) saw 13 of its 14 original scripted series appear on 2018 year-end best lists compiled by critics&#8212;a much higher batting average than competitors like HBO, which saw 20 out of its 70 series represented, or Netflix, which had 62 out of 530 originals on those lists, per FX.</p>\n<p>Landgraf proclaimed again that having a high-quality brand is the best way to cut through the noise of the peak-TV era, especially as streamers proliferate and churn out programming. He also noted, however, that “the enemy of excellence is time. . . . If you want to get things right, you have to stop sometimes. You have to slow down.” This focus on quality, according to Landgraf, is why FX’s highly anticipated adaptation of <em>Y</em>&#8212;which has finally been ordered to series, with <strong>Diane Lane</strong>  starring&#8212;took longer to come to fruition than some fans had hoped it would. “It’s not an easy adaptation; it’s taken a long time to get it right,” Landgraf said. And though Landgraf critiqued Netflix and the tech industry’s “winner-takes-all” attitude, he also noted that he was “really grateful” that FX will soon be part of a powerful streaming platform itself: once Disney acquires Twentieth Century Fox, Disney will hold a 60 percent stake in Hulu.</p>\n<p>This spring, the network will launch <em><a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/fosse-verdon-teaser-trailer-fx-sam-rockwell-michelle-williams\">Fosse/Verdon</a>,</em> a limited series about the creative collaboration and romantic relationship between legendary choreographer and director Bob Fosse (played by <strong>Sam Rockwell</strong>) and Broadway star Gwen Verdon (<strong>Michelle Williams</strong>). The series also boasts mega-talent behind the scenes, including executive producer <strong>Lin-Manuel Miranda,</strong> <em>Hamilton</em> director <strong>Thomas Kail,</strong> <em>Dear Evan Hansen</em> playwright <strong>Steven Levenson,</strong> and <em>The Americans</em> show-runner <strong>Joel Fields,</strong> an alum of one of FX’s greatest hits. The network is also premiering <em>What We Do in the Shadows,</em> a half-hour vampire comedy series based on the movie of the same name by co-creators <strong>Jemaine Clement</strong> and <strong>Taika Waititi.</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Ryan Murphy,</strong> a longtime FX creator who recently decamped to Netflix, may be <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/12/ryan-murphy-netflix-the-politician-jessica-lange\">luring</a> some of his old FX team over to his new shows&#8212;but Landgraf also promised that his network would host more seasons of both <em>American Horror Story</em> and <em>American Crime Story,</em> though he did admit that a planned season of the latter about Hurricane Katrina, which has had a <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/12/annette-bening-american-crime-story-katrina\">long and torturous production process</a>, is now officially dead.</p>\n<p>Of <em>Crime Story,</em> Landgraf said, “We have three or four ideas in active development, with writers at work on them. I couldn’t tell you which one is likely to be ready first.” (We know, though, that another planned season about <strong>Bill Clinton</strong> and <strong>Monica Lewinsky</strong> has <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/04/american-crime-story-lewinsky-ryan-murphy\">also been scuttled</a>. And although Murphy has not pitched any ideas for further seasons of <em>Feud</em>&#8212;at least, not since <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/08/fx-feud-prince-charles-princess-diana\">ditching his <strong>Prince Charles</strong> and Diana-themed season</a>&#8212;Landgraf said, “I wouldn’t be surprised if I get a call about another cycle.”</p>","rubric":"TCA","socialTitle":"FX C.E.O. Fires Shots: “Netflix Is Not Telling You the Whole Story”","socialDescription":"At the Television Critics Association’s winter press tour, John Landgraf knocked Netflix’s viewership numbers—and talked Fosse/Verdon and Ryan Murphy.","seoTitle":"FX C.E.O. Fires Shots: “Netflix Is Not Telling You the Whole Story”","seoDescription":"At the Television Critics Association’s winter press tour, John Landgraf knocked Netflix’s viewership numbers—and talked Fosse/Verdon and Ryan Murphy.","channel":"Hollywood","subChannel":"Television","issueDate":"","ledeCaption":"Penn Badgley in <em>You.