\"https://www.wsj.com/articles/hillary-will-run-again-1541963599?ns=prod/accounts-wsj\">there</a>. Most recently, CNN’s <strong>Jeff Zeleny</strong> <a href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/27/politics/inside-politics-forecast-cnntv/index.html\">reported</a> on that Clinton was once again floating a candidacy to her friends: “[S]he was telling people that look, given all this news from the indictments, particularly the <strong>Roger Stone</strong> indictment, she talked to several people, saying ‘look, I’m not closing the doors to this,’” he said, adding that other associates still were dubious. (Said one: “it would surprise me greatly if she actually did it.”)</p>\n<p>This, said <strong>John Podesta,</strong> Clinton’s 2016 campaign manager, is nonsense. “Look, first of all, I love her, I wish she was president, she got 3 million more votes than <strong>Donald Trump</strong> did, she would have been a great president,” he <a href=\"https://www.axios.com/2020-presidential-election-hillary-clinton-not-running-podesta-070ef325-dd68-480e-98ea-99ebd619d047.html\">said</a> on CNN Tuesday. “But she says she’s not running for president.”</p>\n<p>“I take her at her word,” he continued, adding that the Democratic Party has “got a lot of great candidates out there right now, and I think the Democratic primary”&#8212;already a crowded affair&#8212;”is going to be a spirited one with a lot of great ideas coming forward.” He dismissed the narrative that Clinton was mulling another presidential run as “media catnip.”</p>\n<p>Indeed, there seems to be something irresistible to the media in the idea of Clinton resurfacing. Perhaps it’s simply difficult to imagine that arguably the most qualified candidate to ever run for president is content at the prospect of spending her days <a href=\"https://www.groupon.com/deals/gl-lnc-the-clintons-la-2019\">selling speaking tour tickets on Groupon</a>, or even, as Podesta described, visiting Puerto Rico to “help the people that Donald Trump has abandoned” as the island recovers from Hurricane Maria. Whatever the reason, each new story in the genre is met with an inevitable backlash. The response to the <em>Journal</em> op-ed is a prime example: “Please, Hillary, Don’t Do It,” two CNN contributors <a href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/14/opinions/hillary-2020-prospect-opinion-honan-wierson/index.html\">wrote in panicked response</a>, while <strong>Chris Cilizza</strong> devoted <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_T9hcFrD6Ns\">six-and-a-half minutes</a> to calling it a “terrible idea,” and <a href=\"https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2018/11/no-hillary-clinton-wont-be-the-2020-democratic-nominee.html\">countless</a> <a href=\"https://www.thedailybeast.com/a-request-to-mark-penn-andy-stein-and-any-other-so-called-democrats-talking-up-clinton-2020-respectfully-shut-up\">hot</a> <a href=\"https://theweek.com/articles/807216/hillary-2020-cannot-serious\">takes</a> <a href=\"https://thehill.com/homenews/media/418137-foxs-pirro-to-clinton-on-2020-the-only-place-that-you-need-to-run-is-back-into\">emerged</a> panning possibility. (The one exception was Trump White House adviser <strong>Kellyanne Conway,</strong> who tweeted: <a href=\"https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/conway-jokes-about-prediction-hillary-clinton-will-run-again-in-2020-1.6640531\">“Dear God, please, yes.”</a>)</p>\n<p>But the myth of Clinton as leader-in-exile will persist as long as she remains a public figure, buoyed both by people who believe she would’ve won in 2016 save for a few targeted Russian hacks, and by those who see rumors about her potential run as a characteristic display of unalloyed ambition and hubris. The Clinton persona has become symbolic of the rift in the Democratic Party that paved the way for Trumpism, and rumors of her return are all but guaranteed to trigger meltdowns.</p>\n<h3>More Great Stories from <em>Vanity Fair</em></h3>\n<p>&#8212; The leaking, gossiping, and infighting that <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/trump-aide-recalls-conways-leaking-tactics-in-the-west-wing-vipers-nest?inline\">made Kellyanne Conway a formidable White House player</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; Why old news habits must die&#8212;so that <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/how-the-media-can-prevent-2020-from-becoming-2016?inline\">real journalism can live</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; Nancy Pelosi is America’s most powerful <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/style/photos/2019/01/nancy-pelosi-power-suits?inline\">power-suit boss</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; Is Kamala Harris the <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/kamala-harris-new-2020-democratic-frontrunner-oakland-speech?inline\">2020 candidate to beat?</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; Your passport to <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/behind-the-scenes-hollywood-cover-2019?inline\"><em>Vanity Fair</em>’s 25th Hollywood Issue</a> with Saoirse Ronan, Timothée Chalamet, Chadwick Boseman, and more</p>\n<p>Looking for more? <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/newsletters\">Sign up</a> for our daily Hive newsletter and never miss a story.</p>","rubric":"Democratic Primary 2020","socialTitle":"“Take Her at Her Word”: Hillary Allies Address the 2020 Rumors","socialDescription":"John Podesta offers more “media catnip.”","seoTitle":"“Take Her at Her Word”: Hillary Allies Address the 2020 Rumors","seoDescription":"John Podesta offers more “media catnip.”","channel":"News","subChannel":"Politics","issueDate":"","ledeCaption":"","contentSource":"web","canonicalUrl":"","interactiveOverride":"","contentType":"","textMimeType":"","tags":["hillary clinton","2020","democrats","politics"],"revisionAuthor":"Katie Commisso","meta":{"collectionName":"articles","modelName":"article","publishable":true,"identifiable":true,"image":false,"archived":false,"hallable":true,"hierarchical":false},"id":"5c530137ba532c6650dee079","revision":5,"createdAt":"January 31, 2019 9:07 am","modifiedAt":"January 31, 2019 9:30 am","revisionCreatedAt":"January 31, 2