n":null},"4:3":{"override":false,"height":1500,"width":2000,"modifications":{"crop":{"height":1500,"width":2000,"x":0,"y":0}},"duration":null},"1:1":{"override":false,"height":1787,"width":1787,"modifications":{"crop":{"height":1787,"width":1787,"x":106.5,"y":0}},"duration":null}},"title":"TRUMP SCENE 6A","credit":"By Doug M​ills/The New York Times/Redux.","cropMode":"TOP","meta":{"collectionName":"photos","modelName":"photo","publishable":false,"identifiable":false,"image":true,"archived":false,"hallable":false,"hierarchical":false},"restrictCropping":false,"id":"5c747328836014780ce56ae7","revision":1,"createdAt":"February 25, 2019 5:58 pm","modifiedAt":"February 25, 2019 5:59 pm","revisionCreatedAt":"February 25, 2019 5:59 pm","altText":"TRUMP SCENE 6A","description":"","caption":"","tags":[],"modelName":"photo","collection":"photos"}]},"pubDate":"February 25, 2019 6:01 pm","related":[],"template":"default","url":"/news/2019/02/donald-trump-robert-mueller-special-counsel-report","videos":{}},{"hed":"“She Has a Moralizing to Her”: Is Elizabeth Warren Actually “Unlikable?”","promoHed":"“She Has a Moralizing to Her”: Is Elizabeth Warren Actually “Unlikeable?”","dek":"Women in certain fields endure a different kind of test than men do&#8212;or an additional one. But that doesn’t mean that no woman will pass it, or that disliking a certain woman stems solely from misogyny.","promoDek":"Women in certain fields endure a different kind of test than men do&#8212;or an additional one. But that doesn’t mean that no woman will pass it, or that disliking a certain woman stems solely from misogyny.","body":"<p>From time to time, the political press propagates a thought that, whatever its validity, dominates the discourse. It’s akin to a spontaneous combustion, and the truism it produces lasts until the next one comes along. As in: <strong>Amy Klobuchar’s</strong> two-and-a-half-minute exchange with <strong>Brett Kavanaugh</strong> about his drinking habits gave instant rise to the widespread conclusion that she should be the Democratic nominee.</p>\n<p>And no sooner had <strong>Elizabeth Warren</strong> entered the race in late December than the question of whether she’s “likable” was immediately interpreted as misogynistic.</p>\n<p>Warren’s talents as a campaigner were evident in her foray into Iowa during the first week of January. She’s quite skilled at drilling down to a simple, comprehensible point, usually having to do with economic justice. Her anecdotes go over well. For example, in Iowa she told the story of getting in touch with Iowa Republican Senator <strong>Chuck Grassley,</strong> and <a href=\"https://www.warren.senate.gov/newsroom/press-releases/bipartisan-over-the-counter-hearing-aid-legislation-to-become-law\">working with him</a> to get a bill through Congress that lowered the cost of hearing aids. (Cheers and applause.) She’s earned bragging rights for having spawned the idea&#8212;before she entered the Senate&#8212;of a Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, to protect individuals from scams in credit cards, mortgages, and loans. The new agency was relatively successful, until the Trump administration took over and began to de-fang it.</p>\n<p>But there’s another aspect to Warren’s economic populism&#8212;one that makes her less than popular among her Senate colleagues. This friction has nothing to do with Warren being a woman in politics, or displaying political ambition&#8212;just as much of what bothered people about <strong>Hillary Clinton</strong> had nothing to do with her gender. For an explanation of what it is about Warren that perturbs her colleagues, I sought out an observant former Senate Democratic aide of many years’ standing. What he said echoed comments and stories I’d heard from senators and reporters who’ve dealt with Warren. “She projects a ‘holier than thou’ attitude that her colleagues find irritating. She’s very doctrinaire. She’s somewhat ‘My way or the highway’&#8212;not as much as <strong>Bernie Sanders,</strong> but up there,” he said. “She has a moralizing to her . . . She rails against Wall Street, which may be appealing to some people, but it’s too simplistic to work as an analysis. But she’s very good at finding issues that resonate with middle Americans,” he added, citing the hearing-aid story. He went on: “She’s a little aloof; she’s strong in her convictions, unwilling to bend.”</p>\n<p>He then offered a comparison between Warren and Clinton as senators. Of Warren he said, “She’s never tried very hard to make friends there. Compare that to Hillary: She knew coming into the Senate that she was viewed by many there as the devil incarnate, and she kept her head down and worked to make friends on both sides of the aisle.”</p>\n<p>Of course, despite her best efforts, the “unlikable” tag has also been attached to Clinton. What bothered many people (women, as well as men) about Clinton was that she gave off an attitude of entitlement&#8212;the tin ear and air of superiority that led her to label half of <strong>Donald Trump’s</strong> supporters “a basket of deplorables.” That misogyny dogged Clinton is without question, but some of her own personality traits were responsible for the way she was seen by a substantial segment of the public.</p>\n<p>The fact that Warren’s likability, like Clinton’s, has been questioned has led numerous observers to conclude that no woman in politics can overcome criticism based on her gender. That’s nonsense. After all, a <a href=\"http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/12/18/record-number-women-in-congress/\">record</a> 102 women were elected to the House of Representatives in 2018. (The previous House record was 85 women.) Republicans simply haven’t made the same effort that Democrats have to bring women into their ranks, with the <a href=\"http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/12/18/record-number-women-in-congress/\">result</a> that women now represent 8 percent of House Republicans, as opposed to 38 percent of the Democratic caucus. (Democrats also stressed diversity, and sought out candidates of both genders who’d served in the military.) In the Senate, midterms plus the appointment to fill the remainder of John McCain’s term, added 15 women, for a total of 25 women senators; previously, the <a href=\"http://cawp.rutgers.edu/sites/default/files/resources/results_release_5bletterhead5d_1.pdf\">record</a> was 23. Two incumbent women senators lost to men on clear substantive issues. Midterms also saw women pick up gubernatorial seats, and <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/12/opinion/election-michigan-women-stabenow-whitmer.html\">four of the top statewide offices</a> in Michigan. A black woman fell just short of winning the governorship of Georgia, overtaken at least in part by the fact that her opponent was also the secretary of state who set and twisted the rules of the race. The direction is clear. A country that couldn’t see women through other than a misogynistic lens wouldn’t produce such results.</p>\n<p>Another way to look at Warren’s situation in Congress is to compare it to that of <strong>Nancy Pelosi,</strong> as House Speaker far and away the most powerful woman on Capitol Hill, if not in all of Washington. Despite the attacks on her in national politics&#8212;the right charges her with being a “San Francisco liberal,” though in fact she’s a product of the brass-knuckle politics of Baltimore, where her father was the boss-mayor&#8212;Pelosi’s colleagues don’t raise the issue of her likability. Under pressure from their Republican opponents, some Democrats running for the House for the first time pledged not to support her for Speaker (though not all of them held to this promise). But no serious challenge developed. It was clear, as she skillfully dispatched possible rivals&#8212;who said it was time for fresh blood in the Democratic leadership&#8212;that Pelosi is admired by most of the men as well as the women in the Democratic caucus for her legislative smarts and her toughness wrapped in a certain grace. Several said that Pelosi was just who was needed to deal with Donald Trump. She met the argument of those who said she should make way for younger leadership by agreeing to step down from the Speakership after four more years. The contrasting cases of Warren and Pelosi show that people&#8212;both men and women&#8212;are capable of making distinctions among women in politics.</p>\n<p>The question arises: What does likability matter in politics? Does it&#8212;should it&#8212;matter at all, if someone can get elected? In fact, it counts for a lot in determining whether a political figure can work effectively with others&#8212;whether she or he can build coalitions&#8212;or can lead the public. A politician whom large numbers of people find grating simply has a harder time leading the country. This is one reason I don’t complain about the length of presidential campaigns: It usually helps sort out who will wear well. Usually. The fact that Trump is disliked by a majority of the country has been one factor getting in the way of his possible effectiveness.</p>\n<p>It’s undeniable that, while women have been making headlong progress in politics, as well as in some other professional fields, they still carry an extra burden. The double standard still exists: A man who speaks out strongly or objects to something a male boss has done is “strong,” “tough.” A woman who does the same thing is likely to be termed “difficult.” That word, “difficult,” stated or insinuated, haunts women in the workplace. Fortunately, an increasing proportion of men have enough inner strength or are sufficiently enlightened that they deal with women the same way they do men. Sexism in the workplace and in politics may be fading, but not quickly enough.</p>\n<p>At least for a while longer, women in certain fields will endure a different kind of test than men do&#8212;or an additional one. But that doesn’t mean that no woman will pass it, that it’s the only test applied to women candidates, that people can’t make distinctions, or that disliking a certain woman stems solely from misogyny. Nor does it mean that, like men, women can’t find a female candidate wanting on other grounds.</p>\n<p>Misogyny can certainly affect women in politics, but they’ll also be judged on other factors on a case-by-case basis. Other female candidates warming up for the race warrant scrutiny for other traits. Ultimately, candidates of both genders must grapple with the valid question of “likability,” which will help answer a far more important question: How will they govern?</p>\n<h3>More Great Stories from <em>Vanity Fair</em></h3>\n<p>&#8212; The real story behind the <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/the-real-story-behind-the-havana-embassy-mystery?inline\">Havana embassy sonic “attacks”</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; Meet 2019’s <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/politics-power-players-portfolio?inline\">political power players</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; Is the left lane big enough for both <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/why-bernie-sanders-and-elizabeth-warren-are-the-closest-of-frenemies?inline\">Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren?</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; What the <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/what-the-left-can-learn-from-the-maga-cult?inline\">left can learn from MAGA</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; The pop-culture releases that will <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/12/pop-culture-shows-movies-2019?inline\">save us in 2019</a></p>\n<p>Looking for more? <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/newsletters\">Sign up</a> for our daily Hive newsletter and never miss a story.</p>","rubric":"Elizabeth Warren","socialTitle":"“She Has a Moralizing to Her”: Is Elizabeth Warren Actually “Unlikeable?”","socialDescription":"Women in certain fields endure a different kind of test than men do—or an additional one. But that doesn’t mean that no woman will pass it, or that disliking a certa