"><iframe height=\"315\" width=\"560\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Kh_wQUjeaTk\" allowfullscreen=\"\" allowtransparency=\"true\"> </iframe></div></div><p>Many people in elected posts have copped to using marijuana. The brothers Bush, <strong>Al Gore,</strong> and <strong>Barack Obama</strong> <a href=\"https://www.cnn.com/2016/04/20/politics/politicians-marijuana-talk-about-getting-high-420/index.html\">are just a few</a>. Obama said at a conference for magazine editors in 2008, “When I was a kid, I inhaled frequently. That was the point.” Even human bunion <strong>Newt Gingrich</strong> has said as much: “That was a sign we were alive and in graduate school in that era [circa 1968].” Rather than just seeking “thank you for your candor” points, however, Harris is normalizing use of the drug in an effort to legalize it. In 2017, Harris backed the Marijuana Justice Act, which fellow presidential candidate Senator <strong>Cory Booker</strong> introduced.</p>\n<p>Booker himself broke some news on <em>The Breakfast Club</em> last week. When asking about whether the senator has a girlfriend, Charlamagne was able to extract the words “I got a boo” from the senator, a reference to his <a href=\"https://people.com/politics/cory-booker-says-he-has-a-girlfriend/\">secretly-not-secret girlfriend, <strong>Rosario Dawson</strong></a><strong>.</strong> The host is also credited with getting one of the most genuinely delightful interviews from <strong>Hillary Clinton</strong> during her presidential campaign. <a href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/04/18/hillary-clinton-joins-the-breakfast-club-to-talk-beyonce-hot-sauce-in-her-bag-swag/?utm_term=.8e27e77c2483\">In April 2016</a>, he playfully accused her of “pandering to black people” by claiming to carry hot sauce in her bag for years. “Is it working?” she asked. So please, tonight&#8212;a Monday, good as any other night&#8212;raise a toast to the hardest-hitting journalist in politics.</p>\n<h3