e":"default","url":"/style/2019/02/kamala-harris-charlamagne-tha-god-inhaled","videos":{}},{"hed":"A Convincing <em>True Detective</em> Theory Goes All the Way to the Top","promoHed":"A Convincing <em>True Detective</em> Theory Goes All the Way to the Top","dek":"What the Clintons, chickens, and Cajun caviar have to do with <em>True Detective.</em>","promoDek":"What the Clintons, chickens, and Cajun caviar have to do with <em>True Detective.</em>","body":"<p>In anticipation of the Super Bowl this Sunday, HBO has dropped the latest episode of <em>True Detective</em> online a little early. You can watch Season 3, Episode 5, “If You Have Ghosts,” on HBO Go and other streaming platforms right now. But just make sure you are all caught up before you dive into the latest theory here, because it involves some very important revelations from the latest hour. You can listen to our full dive into the episode, including an interview with cast member <strong>Scoot McNairy,</strong> on the most recent episode of <em>Vanity Fair</em>’s podcast <a href=\"https://megaphone.link/PPY3889133426\"><em>Still Watching: True Detective.</em></a></p>\n<p>But if you’re not ready to listen to that or read the latest theory on whodunnit, we’ll throw up a little warning until you get a chance to watch Episode 5. But we <em>can</em> tease that this latest development will take us all the way to the White House.</p>\n<p>Half the fun of wading into the complicated <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/true-detective-season-3-timeline\">timeline</a> of <em>True Detective</em> is analyzing the theories&#8212;half-baked though they may be. Earlier in the season, we were chasing a solution that was <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/true-detective-who-is-the-killer-amelia-season-3-episode-3-the-big-never\">close to home</a> for the Hays family, but now something much more complicated and juicy has emerged. Enter: Gerald Kindt.</p>\n<h2>ARKANSAS ATTORNEY GENERAL GERALD KINDT</h2>\n<p>One of the most striking scenes in Episode 5 saw Tom Purcell hunched over what is likely a recording of his adult daughter, Julie. Taken at face value, the audio is damning to Tom. Julie accuses her father of hurting Will and taking her. But what does she <em>really</em> say?</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I saw him on the television. Make him leave me alone. Tell him to\nleave me alone. I know what he did. The man on TV acting like my\nfather. Where’s my brother, Will? I don’t know what he did with him.\nWe left him resting. He took me and I’m never coming back. Just leave\nme alone.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>All season, <em>True Detective</em> has been fond of vague pronouns as misdirect to keep the audience guessing. Up until Episode 5, Brett Woodard was referred to as “a Man” in the 1990 timeline simply so we wouldn’t be able to track who was convicted in the Purcell case in 1990. Similarly, here, Julie (if that’s who it is) seems to be talking about Tom, but she <em>could</em> be talking about someone else she saw on the TV. She only says someone is <em>acting</em> like her father. In other words, she could be talking about Gerald Kindt.</p>\n<p>Is Kindt her real father? Not necessarily. Though who knows? We know Lucy slept around, we know the rumors about when Julie was born. But Julie was tiny when she was taken and it’s unclear what she remembers about her life before 1980. More important, there have been indications that someone on the law-and-order side of things has been tampering with the case, which brings us to . . .</p>\n<h2>OFFICER HARRIS JAMES</h2>\n<p>James gets name-dropped in this episode as someone who went missing when the case was reopened in 1990, and several clues&#8212;including a suspiciously familiar ghost in Wayne’s study&#8212;indicate that perhaps Wayne and Roland had something to do with his disappearance. In fact, the show is implying they killed him&#8212;we don’t know why. Most pertinently, Harris James is the officer on the scene at the Woodard house back in 1980 who makes the connection between a bright red backpack and Will Purcell. If the Purcell evidence <em>was</em> planted at the scene in the 80s, Harris could have easily been the one to do it.</p>\n<p>We also know that a key set of fingerprints has gone missing from the case file and a mysterious someone&#8212;either a real cop or someone impersonating one&#8212;has been making inquiries around the neighborhood. It feels likely that James would be acting on the orders of someone higher up, and who better to turn up the heat than a powerful man like Gerald Kindt. One more detail about the Harris angle: in the 2015 story line, Wayne and Roland discuss the fact that Hoyt came to visit Wayne (likely) after Harris James died. Which brings us to . . .</p>\n<h2>HOYT FOODS</h2>\n<p>It’s useful to think of real-world parallels when chewing over this next part, which links Attorney General Gerald Kindt to Lucy Purcell’s old employer: Hoyt Foods. This massive company, which seems to employ many of the Arkansas locals, is a clear stand-in for the real-life Tyson Foods. Both companies are based in Arkansas and got their start with chicken. Tyson Foods has been in the news a good deal lately for <a href=\"https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/01/29/tyson-chicken-recall-rubber-may-contaminate-nuggets-usda-says/2717993002/\">various</a> unsavory <a href=\"https://www.nbcnews.com/business/business-news/poultry-workers-denied-bathroom-breaks-wear-diapers-oxfam-report-n572806\">reasons</a>, but the company was in the news a good deal in the late 70s, 80s, and 90s for its connection to Arkansas’s real attorney general-turned-president: <strong>Bill Clinton.</strong></p>\n<p>The show has already made a few connections between Kindt and Clinton. For one, Clinton <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bypWnBR47Rk\"><em>very</em> famously appeared</a> on <em>The Phil Donahue Show</em> in 1992 and self-righteously clutched his pearls when host <strong>Phil Donahue</strong> dared question the stability of the Clinton marriage. The would-be president got thunderous applause. Kindt also makes a <em>Donahue</em> appearance.</p>\n<p>You don’t need to be an expert in all things Clinton or Arkansas to know that the politician and the state enjoyed an especially messy entanglement between politics and big business in the 80s and 90s. (<a href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/whitewater/timeline.htm?noredirect=on\">Whitewater, anyone?</a>) Tyson Foods C.E.O. Don Tyson had a very cozy relationship with the Clintons. A 1992 <em><a href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1992/03/22/in-arkansas-the-game-is-chicken/6244e0fa-5416-4a6a-bae8-a229b854ed98/?utm_term=.fb189aeea3eb\">Washington Post</a></em> report opened with this evocative lede: “Don Tyson kills 25 million chickens a week on his assembly lines, 10 times as many birds as there are people in Arkansas.” Further down the page: “It would be an overstatement to say that Clinton and Tyson could not have succeeded without each other&#8212;for the most part their relationship has been of mutual benefit, helping Tyson expand his operations and Clinton ascend politically.” In 1994, <em><a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/31/magazine/the-president-s-past.html\">The New York Times</a></em> further investigated the connection:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>“[Clinton] was young and he was impressive,” Tyson recalls. “I don’t\nbelieve we ever talked about his politics; hell, he was a Democrat.”\nTyson put a modest sum of money on Clinton in his yearling race, a\ncongressional run in 1974. Although Clinton lost that election, he\nshowed excellent form, and Tyson backed him again in his successful\n1976 run for state attorney general; and again in 1978, when the\n32-year-old ran as the overwhelming favorite for governor.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Tyson’s support came with what appears to have been a lot of <a href=\"https://www.thefiscaltimes.com/Columns/2016/02/02/Why-37-Year-Old-Clinton-Financial-Scandal-Still-Relevant\">leniency and kickbacks</a> from the Clinton administration and even messier entanglements including, what else, an <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/18/us/top-arkansas-lawyer-helped-hillary-clinton-turn-big-profit.html\">investment scandal</a> for <strong>Hillary Clinton.</strong></p>\n<p>Before you start any silly “lock them up” chants, let’s focus back on <em>True Detective.</em> It’s safe to assume the show could easily connect the shadowy billionaire owner of Hoyt Foods with Gerald Kindt. And if he’s involved somehow, everything Hoyt has done so far to stymy both the 1980 investigation and the 1990 re-investigation makes sense. But what on earth is the motivation here?</p>\n<p>Some eagle-eyed Redditors noticed a connection between a portrait of Hoyt’s daughter and missing granddaughter in Episode 3 and a <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sZinAVMvdI8\">behind-the-scenes shot</a> of Devil’s Den in a video HBO released about shooting the show in Arkansas. It’s easy enough to imagine a scenario where Hoyt’s daughter&#8212;driven mad with grief over having lost her own daughter&#8212;might snatch Julie Purcell. Will would be collateral damage. Almost every investigator agrees Will’s death looked like an accident. Perhaps he cracked his head open trying to get his sister back. Perhaps Hoyt’s daughter lured Julie and Will into the woods with shiny toys, corn-husk dolls, and elaborate fantasies about being a secret princess. Perhaps this is the mysterious white woman many Arkansas locals spotted in a fancy brown car. Wouldn’t a chicken heiress drive a fancy car? But did she do it alone?</p>\n<h2>SAM WHITEHEAD</h2>\n<p>All reports of that shifty-looking white woman also mention a black man with a scar or “dead eye” along with her. When questioned about it, Sam brings up the killing line at Hoyt Foods as a likely place for someone to get injured. A one point, Wayne suggests they cross-reference the fingerprints found on the toys in the woods with the men who have been injured at Hoyt Foods. He might be onto something there. Hell, it might even be Sam himself. But that’s not all.</p>\n<h2>LUCY PURCELL</h2>\n<p>In this week’s episode, Wayne draws a connection between Lucy Purcell and the ransom note. Both use the phrase “children should laugh.” He suggests maybe she just wrote the ransom to calm Tom down and ensure he would stop worrying about Julie. But did she do that of her own accord? Out of concern for Tom? Unlikely. A compelling theory is that Lucy was somehow involved in the disappearance of the kids and that maybe, just maybe, she willingly sold them to Hoyt&#8212;her former employer. Maybe her cousin Dan helped her do it. Maybe she genuinely convinced herself that Will and Julie would have a better life with such a rich family. Certainly she didn’t think Will would die. That never seemed to be part of anyone’s plan.</p>\n<p>Did Lucy sleep with Kindt? Is he the real father? Does that embolden him to act on behalf of the Hoyt family? Oh, maybe. If we’re making real-life comparisons already, then we might as well mention “<a href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/08/01/republicans-differ-on-whether-troopergate-remains-a-scandal-for-clinton/?utm_term=.78ccc8b75d96\">Troopergate</a>” and Bill Clinton’s particular sexual appetites when he held high office in Arkansas. In Episode 4, Amelia overhears Lucy wrapping up a call: “Don’t call,” Lucy says. “Who the fuck do you think you’re talking to, motherfucker? Huh? Hello? Hello?” She then tells Amelia that theirs was “not a happy home” (no duh) and that all she could hope for was that her kids would have a better life than she did. But that she messed that up.</p>\n<p>It’s not concrete proof by any stretch, but here’s one more piece of compelling evidence from a <a href=\"https://megaphone.link/PPY3889133426\"><em>Still Watching: True Detective</em></a> listener. Lucy, Tom, Will, and Julie Purcell all shared an unhappy home on Shoepick Lane. (The camera has lingered on that street sign more than once.) In <strong>Nic Pizzolatto’s</strong> home state of Louisiana, there’s an alternative name for bowfins, which are considered largely flavorless, “trash” fish. The Cajuns call them “choupiques,” pronounced guess how?</p>\n<p>Intriguingly, choupiques are <a href=\"https://www.houmatoday.com/entertainment/20090405/choupique-may-be-a-trash-fish-for-some-treasure-to-others\">commercially harvested</a> for their roe to produce Cajun caviar. A “trash” fish with extremely valuable eggs? Gotcha.</p>","rubric":"","socialTitle":"A Convincing True Detective Theory Goes All the Way to the Top","socialDescription":"What the Clintons, chickens, and Cajun caviar have to do with True Detective.","seoTitle":"A Convincing True Detective Theory Goes All the Way to the Top","seoDescription":"What the Clintons, chickens, and Cajun caviar have to do with True Detective.","channel":"Hollywood","subChannel":"Television","issueDate":"","ledeCaption":"","contentSource":"web","canonicalUrl":"","interactiveOverride":"","contentType":"","textMimeType":"","tags":["true detective"],"revisionAuthor":"Rachel Freeman","meta":{"collectionName":"articles","modelName":"article","publishable":true,"identifiable":true,"image":false,"archived":false,"hallable":true,"hierarchical":false},"id":"5c5217833889055ec0570bb0","revision":46,"createdAt":"January 30, 2019 4:30 pm","modifiedAt":"February 1, 2019 4:48 pm","revisionCreatedAt":"February 1, 2019 4:48 pm","_embedded":{"categories-channels":[{"fields":{"name":"Hollywood","slug":"hollywood","revisionAuthor":"aviator-scripts-categories-migration","meta":{"collectionName":"categories","modelName":"category","publishable":false,"identifiable":false,"image":false,"archived":false,"hallable":false,"hierarchical":true},"id":"5ae9f11fae03af0739cf33e0","revision":0,"createdAt":"May 2, 2018 1:10 pm","modifiedAt":"May 2, 2018 1: