,"parent":[],"photos":{},"root":[],"slug":"white-house"}]},"contributors":{"author":[{"id":"557f2142320a56cf42411484","modelName":"contributor","collection":"contributors","bio":"Tina Nguyen is a reporter for The Hive, covering politics and the media.","email":"","name":"Tina Nguyen","socialMedia":[{"network":"Twitter","handle":"Tina_Nguyen"}]}]},"inlineEmbeds":[],"photos":{"tout":[{"revisionAuthor":"Benjamin Landy","filename":"Trump-Alone-Time.jpg","aspectRatios":{"master":{"width":2000,"height":1334,"format":"JPEG","duration":null,"url":"https://cn-copilot-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/vf/production/2019/02/04/5c5865d7b6173e6d16293f18_Trump-Alone-Time.jpg"},"3:2":{"override":false,"height":1332,"width":1998,"modifications":{"crop":{"height":1332,"width":1998,"x":1,"y":0}},"duration":null},"5:3":{"override":false,"height":1200,"width":2000,"modifications":{"crop":{"height":1200,"width":2000,"x":0,"y":0}},"duration":null},"2:3":{"override":false,"height":1332,"width":888,"modifications":{"crop":{"height":1332,"width":888,"x":556,"y":0}},"duration":null},"9:16":{"override":false,"height":1328,"width":747,"modifications":{"crop":{"height":1328,"width":747,"x":626.5,"y":0}},"duration":null},"7:3":{"override":false,"height":855,"width":1995,"modifications":{"crop":{"height":855,"width":1995,"x":2.5,"y":0}},"duration":null},"16:9":{"override":false,"height":1125,"width":2000,"modifications":{"crop":{"height":1125,"width":2000,"x":0,"y":0}},"duration":null},"4:3":{"override":false,"height":1332,"width":1776,"modifications":{"crop":{"height":1332,"width":1776,"x":112,"y":0}},"duration":null},"1:1":{"override":false,"height":1334,"width":1334,"modifications":{"crop":{"height":1334,"width":1334,"x":333,"y":0}},"duration":null}},"title":"AFP_1CO7O9","credit":"By Alex Edelman/AFP/Getty Images.","cropMode":"TOP","meta":{"collectionName":"photos","modelName":"photo","publishable":false,"identifiable":false,"image":true,"archived":false,"hallable":false,"hierarchical":false},"restrictCropping":false,"id":"5c5865d7b6173e6d16293f19","revision":1,"createdAt":"February 4, 2019 11:18 am","modifiedAt":"February 4, 2019 11:18 am","revisionCreatedAt":"February 4, 2019 11:18 am","altText":"AFP_1CO7O9","description":"Getty; 1089548434","caption":"Trump departs the Oval Office, January 25, 2019.","tags":[],"modelName":"photo","collection":"photos"}]},"pubDate":"February 4, 2019 11:15 am","related":[],"template":"default","url":"/news/2019/02/the-worst-kept-secret-of-trumps-presidency","videos":{}},{"hed":"The Bernie Conundrum: Can “Salty as Ever” Sanders Leverage His Supporters, Quash His Haters, and Play Nice Enough with Former Foes to Be a Real 2020 Player?","promoHed":"The Bernie Conundrum: Can “Salty as Ever” Sanders Leverage His Supporters, Quash His Haters, and Play Nice Enough with Former Foes to Be a Real 2020 Player?","dek":"Whether Sanders can fully realize his presidential ambitions the second time around is an open question. But Sanders knows that as much as people loathe the two political parties, those parties also remain the two most powerful vehicles in the war for ideas in 2020. It’s an essential truth about our moment that could also leave Howard Schultz out in the cold, hoping to pay off the bouncer to get in to the party.","promoDek":"Whether Sanders can fully realize his presidential ambitions the second time around is an open question. But Sanders knows that as much as people loathe the two political parties, those parties also remain the two most powerful vehicles in the war for ideas in 2020. It’s an essential truth about our moment that could also leave Howard Schultz out in the cold, hoping to pay off the bouncer to get in to the party.","body":"<section class=\"content-section\" data-type=\"section\"><p>In June 2000, Rage Against the Machine delivered a music video for their single “Testify,” a big track off their album <em>The Battle of Los Angeles.</em> It was a shotgun blast. At the time, just a year before 9/11, pop music might have been at its creative nadir, the Billboard charts painted with a tableau of barely-remembered artists who couldn’t be bothered by political commentary: <strong>Sisqó,</strong> Creed, <strong>Rob Thomas</strong> and <strong>Santana,</strong> Savage Garden, and various musicians who wore carpenter jeans and frosted tips. Rage wasn’t playing that game. The nation was slouching toward a showdown between <strong>George W. Bush</strong> and <strong>Al Gore,</strong> two white men in suits racing to the mushy middle.</p>\n<p>With <strong>Michael Moore</strong> directing, Rage used their video to hammer Bush and Gore as two sides of the same centrist coin, a pair of incrementalist politicians beholden to a corrupt system that favored Wall Street billionaires and entrenched-power elites. Given the history that would unfold in the coming years across the Levant, it was a facile argument in hindsight. But politics at that time, before the World Trade Center fell, was defined by complacency and disinterest. Rage declared their answer to this broken system at the conclusion of their music video for “Testify”: an endorsement of <strong>Ralph Nader,</strong> the consumer-rights advocate and Green Party nominee who proclaimed that, “If you’re not turned onto politics, politics will turn on you.” Other celebrities at the time, like <strong>Susan Sarandon, Eddie Vedder,</strong> and <strong>Ben Harper,</strong> lined up behind Nader. He would go on to win 2.8 million votes, only a slice of the national count. But Nader had enough cultural buzz and disaffected supporters on the left to capture almost 100,000 votes in Florida, tipping the presidency in Bush’s direction with an assist from <strong>Pat Buchanan.</strong></p>\n<p>Almost 20 years later, another third-party spoiler has entered the presidential fray. His name is <strong>Howard Schultz,</strong> the self-made billionaire founder of Starbucks. No one, however, will be making a music video about Howard Schultz. Politicians only seep into pop culture when they inspire people, and Schultz, with his hand-gesturing boardroom speak and glaring lack of agenda, is so far only inspiring rage tweets from Democrats who don’t want him to help <strong>Donald Trump</strong> get re-elected. That isn’t stopping Schultz from moving forward. In a Medium <a href=\"https://medium.com/@Howardschultz/ourpath-9164e18bdb98\">post</a> published Tuesday, Schultz wrote that he feels “a deep responsibility and moral obligation to address Americans’ frustrations with our broken two-party system.” Despite the criticisms, he wrote, “I’m excited to keep the conversation going,” the ultimate piece of charmless corporate jargon.</p>\n<p>But Tuesday brought another piece of news that reminds us why Schultz faces such long odds if he chooses to run: the entrance of <strong>Bernie Sanders</strong> into the Democratic presidential race. As Sanders and Trump demonstrated in 2016, insurgent politics today is practiced inside the contours of the two-party system, not outside of it. In an era of extreme partisanship, all of the action in American politics, the darkness and the fun alike, is taking place inside the tents of the two major parties. Whether Sanders can fully realize his presidential ambitions the second time around is an open question. But Sanders knows that as much as people loathe the two political parties, those parties also remain the two most important vehicles in the war for power and ideas in 2020. It’s an essential truth about our moment that could leave Schultz out in the cold, hoping to pay off the bouncer to get in to the party.</p>\n</section><section class=\"content-section\" data-type=\"section\"><p>Given their behavior and tactics to date, Sanders and Schultz, two boys from Brooklyn, are gambling with two very different theories about politics. Both theories have their limits, but Sanders seems to have a better understanding of the state of play as the curtain rises on the 2020 presidential race. Schultz, if he runs, appears to be campaigning from the inside out, a fully-realized American power elite portraying himself as a truth-telling outsider. His media strategy from the get-go seemed the very definition of Amtrak-corridor conventional: a book tour, a <em>60 Minutes</em> interview, sit-downs with <em>Morning Joe</em> and the <em>Goop</em> podcast. None of it screamed populist. As he stepped out into the public crossfire, Schultz wasn’t talking about his rags-to-riches story or his admirable efforts to bring health care to thousands of low-wage earners. Instead, he was lashing both parties for abandoning the centrist impulses of the “silent majority”&#8212;a plurality, if anything&#8212;that was predictably silent when the Twitter mobs immediately came for his head.</p>\n<p>Schultz has a right to tell his story and deserves not to be dismissed out of hand simply because he is a billionaire. The angry question of “What have you ever done?” thrown at Schultz by the online hordes can be equally applied to any number of backbencher politicians and professional activists who are here for the re-tweets. But Schultz misfired by broaching the idea of a third-party candidacy at a time when the public is questioning the very idea of whether billionaires should exist. Those criticisms might have been blunted had he brought a big idea or two to the table. <strong>Ross Perot</strong> and Nader both had proactive agendas and passionate pet issues that defined their candidacies, which didn’t rest solely on trashing their opponents. As a consequence, both Perot and Nader managed to have an outsized impact with voters despite the electoral futility of their campaigns. Schultz, instead, has been little more than a scold, chiding the very politicians who are bringing actual ideas to the table.</p>\n<p>Schultz’s other big mistake was suggesting a third-party bid, claiming a hunger in the country for something other than the menu offerings from Democrats and Republicans. It is true that roughly a third of the country identifies as moderate, according to a recent Pew survey, suggesting a lane for Schultz (or his political consultants). But what Schultz seems not to understand is that in an era of partisan sorting, moderates, too, are choosing sides. For the most part, they are drifting into the Democratic Party, which recaptured the House of Representatives last November not because of firebrand liberals like <strong>Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez,</strong> but on the backs of suburban moderates hailing from places like Orange County and central Virginia. Moderates do have power. At the moment, they’re just choosing to vote Democrat in opposition to President Trump. What’s more, the idea that registered partisans might abandon their party in the ballot box in favorite of a sensible moderate is increasingly quaint. As the political scientist <strong>Lee Drutman</strong> has written, partisan identity in the age of Trump is much more closely aligned with social and cultural identity. That lends a more intense meaning to your partisan jersey, red team or blue. Common ground is much more difficult to locate outside of the two parties. If Schultz wanted an honest hearing at a time of deep partisan divide, the Democratic primary would have been the most logical place for it. Followed, of course, by a CNN town hall.</p>\n</section><section class=\"content-section\" data-type=\"section\"><p>While Schultz runs from the inside out, Sanders seems to be reprising the strategy that almost got him to the pinnacle in 2016, running from the outside in, a people-powered ideologue gunning to take over a Democratic Party that still regards him with suspicion. The very fact that Sanders was not fully accepted into the ranks of the Democratic establishment is one source of his appeal.</p>\n<p>Sanders might be 77 years old and “salty as ever,” as CNN’s <strong>Kate Bolduan</strong> said on-air Tuesday after his announcement, but he’s still a central figure in the dialectic of the Democratic Party, its most uncompromising ideological figure, and best fund-raiser. Like Trump, Sanders didn’t get there by climbing the ladder in Washington like his fellow senators now in the presidential race; he did it by tapping into common-sense ideas about economic fairness and raising oceans of small-donor cash online in the process. He delivered his message using non-traditional media and waited for the green-room journalism crowd to catch up. A democratic socialist, Sanders might have chosen to run in 2016 as a third-party liberal in the mold of Nader. But instead, he smartly decided to disrupt the Democratic Party from the inside by seeking its presidential nomination, all while never calling himself a Democrat. Sanders became the liberal folk hero of the last campaign, the subject of graffiti murals, hipster endorsements, and D.I.Y. merch, the cool grassroots signifiers that swirled around Nader a decade and a half earlier.</p>\n<p>While Sanders lost to <strong>Hillary Clinton,</strong> his failed campaign nevertheless established his place in the political firmament. Today, as he embarks on a new race, his signature issues are now key touchstones in the Democratic primary. When his rivals tip-toe around their commitment to Medicare for all, a new minimum wage, and free college education, Sanders will be right there holding their feet to the fire. And as curmudgeonly as Sanders seems, he also likes the attention from a mainstream press that ignored him for so many decades, which is why he could barely conceal his smiles during his announcement interview with <strong>John Dickerson</strong> on <em>CBS This Morning.</em> Sanders can’t wait to go back on <em>Ellen</em> and hang out with <strong>Killer Mike.</strong> He is able to do all of these things precisely because he isn’t a creature of the Democratic establishment&#8212;because he is disruptive and refuses to play by the rules. So why not run it back in 2020?</p>\n<p>Sanders’s biggest failure in 2016 was not building coalitions. He found it difficult to expand his reach beyond liberals, white workers, and young people, to win over the older women and African-Americans who eventually gave their votes to Clinton. But on CBS, Sanders told Dickerson that unlike in 2016, he can plausibly win the nomination without cobbling together a majority of Democrats. “In some ways it makes it easier,” Sanders said. “When you’re running against one person you know you gotta have 51 percent of the votes. Now who knows what you need? Thirty, thirty-five percent?”</p>\n<p>That may come to pass: Trump slowly grew his campaign throughout the Republican primaries when many pundits expected him to top out around 25 percent. But just as Republicans don’t behave as Democrats, Democrats don’t behave as Republicans. The impulses and issue sets are different, and Sanders has yet to convince Democrats beyond his base of economic progressives that he cares deeply about the plight of immigrants, criminal-justice reform, and the white-hot cultural issues that are roiling our politics under Trump. It would be glib, though, to suggest Sanders hasn’t learned from his mistakes. He has a chance to convince Democrats he’s evolved, even if Democrats now have many more choices than they did when it was just Bernie versus Hillary all day every day.</p>\n<p>Sanders’s outsider patina gave him power in 2016 and it will again in this campaign. But he can no longer wield the element of surprise. Sanders made plenty of enemies in the Democratic Party, in and around Clinton’s campaign specifically. There are legions of well-connected Democrats who do not like Sanders and would rather he spend the rest of his days slurping down Ben &amp; Jerry’s in Burlington. They will plant negative stories about him, steer money to other candidates, puff up his rivals, and happily let him twist in the wind when he stumbles. Those things might not matter to his die-hard supporters, but every successful Democratic nominee after <strong>Jimmy Carter</strong> played nice with party insiders in pursuit of the ring. Even <strong>Elizabeth Warren</strong> has met with <strong>Jamie Dimon.</strong></p>\n<p>Sanders seems like he’d rather watch a 10-hour <em>Bachelor</em> marathon, <em>Clockwork Orange</em>&#8211;style, than do the same. He is permanently averse to playing the inside political game, gabbing with power brokers on the phone, or charming the media off-the-record. His sequel campaign will test whether those choices matter anymore, whether big speeches, lofty policy ideas, and social media alone can carry the day. This might be a Very <strong>Bill Simmons</strong> Hot Take, but Sanders is the <strong>James Harden</strong> of politics. He’ll get you 30 points a night, but it’s hard to see how he wins a championship without getting his teammates involved. Either way, he’ll still be in the conversation.</p>\n<p><em>Peter Hamby is the host of Snapchat’s</em> Good Luck America.</p>\n</section>","rubric":"2020","socialTitle":"The Bernie Conundrum: Can “Salty as Ever” Sanders Be a Real 2020 Player?","socialDescription":"Whether Sanders can fully realize his presidential ambitions the second time around is an open question. But Sanders knows that as much as people loathe the two political parties, those parties also remain the two most powerful vehicles in the war for ideas in 2020. It’s an essential truth about our moment that could also leave Howard Schultz out in the cold, hoping to pay off the bouncer to get in to the party.","seoTitle":"The Bernie Conundrum: Can “Salty as Ever” Sanders Leverage His Supporters, Quash His Haters, and Play Nice Enough with Former Foes to Be a Real 2020 Player?","seoDescription":"Whether Sanders can fully realize his presidential ambitions the second time around is an open question. But Sanders knows that as much as people loathe the two political parties, those parties also remain the two most powerful vehicles in the war for ideas