greatest trade ever,” George Soros made the “trade of the century,” betting against the British pound and earning a billion dollars in a single day. On the losing side of Soros’s wager was none other than Her Majesty’s Treasury, which lost British taxpayers more than three billion pounds on that “Black Wednesday” in September 1992. Soros, until then relatively unknown beyond investor and philanthropic circles, was bestowed overnight fame and the honor of the “Man Who Broke the Bank of England.”\n<p>But the similarities between Paulson and Soros end at their greatest trades. At age 13, after the Nazis had taken Budapest, Soros went into hiding, posing as the godson of a Ministry of Agriculture inspector, then survived the Battle of Budapest (40,000 of his neighbors didn’t). At 13, Paulson was kicking around tidy Beechhurst, Queens, selling Charms candies at a markup to his classmates and discovering the charms of capitalism.</p>\n<p>After graduation and a brief stint working as a traveling salesman for a fine goods wholesaler along the Welsh coast, Soros talked his way into a job as a clerk at the merchant bank Singer &amp; Friedlander, making his way to New York two years later. By 1970, he’d started Soros Fund Management, which would earn its lucky investors an average annual 20 percent return rate for four decades to follow. Paulson may have made more on his subprime bet ($3.7 billion) than Soros made on his British pounds wager ($1 billion), but we’ll see if Paulson can match the consistency and longevity of “the Great Speculator.”</p>","socialMedia":[],"photos":{"tout":[{"aspectRatios":{"master":{"width":1400,"height":700,"format":"JPEG","url":"https://cn-copilot-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/vf/production/2016/06/02/5750385449ce0b0f6da47f57_hive-contributor-profile-george-soros.jpg"}},"revisionCreatedAt":"June 2, 2016 9:45 am","meta":{"collectionName":"photos","modelName":"photo","image":true},"revisionAuthor":"Kelly Butler","filename":"hive-contributor-profile