ritz and walk towards, anticipant&#8212;signal something different. Escape and identity. That invisible shroud that announces us or lingers like a calling card: <em>she was just here</em>.</p>\n<p>Dreary late winter is the perfect time to be transported. D.S., from D.S. &amp; Durga, offers warmth with saffron and gardenia, while Tory Burch’s Fou de Toi, inspired by the memory of powerful love, brings a different kind of heat. Papier Carbone from Ormaie, a natural brand that launched late last year, captures the scent of carbon writing paper once used in French classrooms. Chanel Les Exclusifs 1957 bestows a timeless comfort: musk, vanilla, honey.</p>\n<p>For Alessandro Michele’s latest Gucci collection, The Alchemist’s Garden, scents play games with our imagination. Leather-bound, as if meant to dust off before opening, they tell a story inspired by the rare-specific of childhood stuff. A Song for the Rose, for instance, is an ode to Michele’s mother, who “used to have a beautiful deep blue vintage perfume bottle in her bathroom, filled with rose essence.” Vivid imagery and the vague ache required for memorializing these moments is Gucci’s sweet spot, after all. But what also interests Michele is how each fragrance will be interpreted by its wearer: the personal feelings evoked, the memories both material and made-up.</p>\n<p>Similarly, Imaginary Authors characterizes their fragrances as “layered narratives,” with each scent centered on an imagined book by an author who doesn’t exist (their boxes look like books, too!). The recurring plot? What’s personal, what intoxicates, what transports. Its founder, Josh Meyer, remembers traveling to Black Forest in Germany as a child. The scent memory of the place returns to him “over and over again,” even if Meyer spends his days in Portland, Oregon, now. Coastal forests his own Proustian madeleine. Fragrances like Saint Julep (a mint field in Mississippi) or Cape Heartache (the pine resin and fog of Meyer’s Pacific Northwest) are scents that encourage the creation of personal fictions: a nudge to imagine not just what <em>has</em> been, but what might have been. What may be. A scent’s spatiotemporal power can create the unreal as well as the remembered, and to spritz on a new perfume is a transformative step for the person who might see herself as a character&#8212;who’s always known there’s more than meets the eye.</p>\n<p><strong>GUCCI the Alchemist’s Garden a Song for the Rose, $330,</strong> <a href=\"https://www.saksfifthavenue.com/Gucci/Beauty/Beauty/The-Alchemist-s-Garden/shop/_/N-1z12vmjZ52flojZ52kjkw?sre=dlpguccimainm1s1l1\">saksfifthavenue.com</a></p>\n<p><strong>D.S. &amp; Durga D.S., $350,</strong> available February 5 at <a href=\"https://dsanddurga.com/\">dsanddurga.com</a></p>\n<p><strong>Ormaie Papier Carbone, $270,</strong> <a href=\"https://www.barneys.com/product/ormaie-papier-carbone-100ml-506117220.html/\">barneys.com</a></p>\n<p><strong>Imaginary Authors Saint Julep, $95,</strong>  <a href=\"https://imaginaryauthors.com/\">imaginaryauthors.com</a></p>\n<p><strong>Tory Burch Love Relentlessly Fou de Toi, $120,</strong> <a href=\"https://www.ulta.com/love-relentlessly-fou-de-toi-eau-de-parfum?productId=pimprod2002662\">ulta.com</a></p>\n<p><strong>Chanel Les Exclusifs 1957, $350,</strong>  available at Chanel New York flagship</p>\n<h3>More Great Stories from <em>Vanity Fair</em></h3>\n<p>&#8212; Nothing says grace like <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2019/01/justin-bieber-face-tattoo-grace?inline\">Justin Bieber’s face tattoo</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; Meghan Markle’s <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2018/12/inside-the-meghan-markle-family-breakdown-thomas-samantha-markle?inline\">fractured family story</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; Inside Trump’s <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/trump-marla-and-the-epic-battle-for-mar-a-lago?inline\">epic battle for Mar-a-Lago</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; Saoirse Ronan’s <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/20