 away peacefully after a short illness with those closest to him by his side.”</p>\n<p>Finney, born in Lancashire, was a formally trained actor who studied at the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art, a classic stomping ground that counts actors like <strong>Kenneth Branagh</strong> and <strong>Anthony Hopkins</strong> among its notable alumni. But Finney didn’t have great aspirations upon enrollment. “There was no burning ambition to be an actor,” he told <a href=\"https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/this-might-possibly-be-albert-finney-107130/\"><em>Rolling Stone</em></a> in 1982 of his decision to pursue drama. “I thought, this is fine, I enjoy it. And there was no sense of going to get away; I was not shaking the provincial dust off my feet, because I didn’t suspect there was any.”</p>\n<p>Nevertheless, the young actor’s talent was instantly apparent. He quickly delved into film, making his debut in the 1960 Laurence Olivier drama <em>The Entertainer.</em> Stardom came soon after when Finney took the titular role in <em>Tom Jones,</em> the unconventional 1963 comedy about a lively young man in 18th-century England. The film earned Finney the first of five Oscar nominations; his last one arrived in 2001, for best supporting actor in <em>Erin Brockovich.</em> (Finney never ended up winning a statuette, though.) Where most actors would immediately move on to a new project after earning acclaim with a film like <em>Tom Jones,</em> Finney took the entire year off, <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/1983/12/04/movies/for-albert-finney-risk-is-everything.html\">declining roles</a> so he could instead go sail on the Pacific.</p>\n<p>Finney also starred in a slew of other memorable films, including <em>Murder on the Orient Express</em> (1974), playing Hercule Poirot, and <em>Big Fish.</em> He also lent his presence to big-budget actions films, including the 2012 James Bond movie <em>Skyfall</em> and <em>The Bourne Ultimatum.</em> Finney crisscrossed between theater and television as well, earning a Laurence Olivier Award, two Tony nominations, and an Emmy (for his portrayal of Winston Churchill in the 2002 TV movie <em>The Gathering Storm</em>). For all his acclaim, he was once offered the honorary title of CBE; he <a href=\"https://infoweb.newsbank.com/resources/doc/nb/news/10035F4843A2700C?p=UKNB\">turned it down</a>, because he felt it “perpetuates snobbery.”</p>\n<p>The actor married three times over the course of his life, first to actress Jane Wenham (with whom he had a son, <strong>Simon</strong>), then French film star <strong>Anouk Aimée,</strong> and then Pene Delmage.</p>\n<p>In a 1983 interview with <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/1983/12/04/movies/for-albert-finney-risk-is-everything.html\"><em>The New York Times</em></a>, Finney once mused about the difficulties of working in theater. “All the effort, all the struggle and sacrifice of an actor and everyone in a theater company goes into creating a momentary illusion. It is like a dream, and when it’s over, it’s over. Gone.” However, he added, “what a lot of people spend their lives doing may not add up to a hill of beans. But their love, effort, and devotion goes into doing it, and it becomes worthwhile.”</p>\n<h3>More Great Stories from <em>Vanity Fair</em></h3>\n<p>&#8212; The <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/02/the-worst-kept-secret-of-trumps-presidency?inline\">worst-kept secret</a> of Trump’s presidency</p>\n<p>&#8212; Is Silicon Valley suffocating the media? <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/how-google-and-facebook-are-strangling-their-digital-offspring?inline\">Jill Abramson weighs in</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; Bernie Sanders’s <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/bernie-sanders-estate-tax-billionaires?inline\">plan to eat the rich</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; The 25 <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/25-best-movie-scenes?inline\">most influential movie scenes</a> of the past 25 years</p>\n<p>&#8212; <em>Broad City</em> and the <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/broad-city-millennial-rage-ilana-glazer-abbi-jacobson?inline\">pivot to millennial rage</a></p>\n<p>Looking for more? <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/newsletters\">Sign up</a> for our daily Hollywood newsletter and never miss a story.</p>","rubric":"obit","socialTitle":"Albert Finney, Oscar-Nominated Star of Murder on the Orient Express, Tom Jones, Dies at 82","socialDescription":"The actor’s family said he died after a short illness.","seoTitle":"Albert Finney, Oscar-Nominated Star of Murder on the Orient Express, Tom Jones, Dies at 82","seoDescription":"The actor’s family said he died after a short illness.","channel":"Hollywood","subChannel":"Movies","issueDate":"","ledeCaption":"","contentSource":"web","canonicalUrl":"","interactiveOverride":"","contentType":"","textMimeType":"","tags":["obituaries","murder on the orient express"],"revisionAuthor":"Cynthia Orgel","meta":{"collectionName":"articles","modelName":"article","publishable":true,"identifiable":true,"image":false,"archived":false,"hallable":true,"hierarchical":false},"id":"5c5d8fe750f462477e50dcd9","revision":54,"createdAt":"February 8, 2019 9:19 am","modifiedAt":"February 8, 2019 10:54 am","revisionCreatedAt":"February 8, 2019 10:54 am","_embedded":{"categories-channels":[{"fields":{"name":"Hollywood","slug":"hollywood","revisionAuthor":"aviator-scripts-categories-migration","meta":{"collectionName":"categories","modelName":"category","publishable":false,"identifiable":false,"image":false,"archived":false,"hallable":false,"hierarchical":true},"id":"5ae9f11fae03af0739cf33e0","revision":0,"createdAt":"May 2, 2018 1:10 pm","modifiedAt":"May 2, 2018 1:10 pm","revisionCreatedAt":"May 2, 2018 1:10 pm","modelName":"category","collection":"categories","contributors":{},"photos":{},"hierarchy":[],"parent":[],"root":[]}},{"fields":{"name":"Movies","slug":"movies","revisionAuthor":"aviator-scripts-categories-migration","meta":{"collect