and was never seen again. After initially denying it had any knowledge of the matter, the Kingdom <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/jamal-khashoggi-killing-a-timeline-of-the-saudis-shifting-story-2018-10#the-whereabouts-of-khashoggis-body-are-unknown-18\">admitted</a> Khashoggi had died inside the consulate, first claiming it happened in a fistfight, and later saying his killing was, in fact, <a href=\"https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45979507\">pre-meditated</a>. All of this, plus the conclusion by the C.I.A. that Crown Prince <strong>Mohammed bin Salman</strong> had <a href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/cia-concludes-saudi-crown-prince-ordered-jamal-khashoggis-assassination/2018/11/16/98c89fe6-e9b2-11e8-a939-9469f1166f9d_story.html\">ordered the assassination</a> of a U.S. resident, should have resulted in the president of the United States punishing, or at the very least condemning, the de facto leader but of course <a href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/02/13/trump-shields-saudi-crown-prince/?utm_term=.13bad6df1f92\">he did nothing of the sort</a>. Anyway, Trump’s good buddy <strong>Tom Barrack</strong> was asked about the whole thing at a Milken Institute summit in Abu Dhabi on Tuesday, and <a href=\"https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-13/colony-s-barrack-says-criticism-of-khashoggi-murder-a-mistake\">here’s what he had to say</a>:</p>\n<p>“Whatever happened in Saudi Arabia, the atrocities in America are equal or worse to the atrocities in Saudi Arabia. . . . The atrocities in any autocratic country are dictated by the rule of law. So for us to dictate what we think is the moral code there when we have a young man and a regime that’s trying to push themselves into 2030 I think is a mistake.”</p>\n<div class=\"embed block row iframe\"><div class=\"wrapper\"><div class=\"embed iframe-embed-component \" data-type=\"iframe\" data-url=\"https://shows.cadence13.com/player/inside-the-hive/episodes/cfc76f84-a44f-4420-b825-6b55c781fab4?customColor=%23ff0000\"><iframe height=\"250\" width=\"100%\" src=\"https://shows.cadence13.com/player/inside-the-hive/episodes/cfc76f84-a44f-4420-b825-6b55c781fab4?customColor=%23ff0000\"></iframe></div></div></div><p><strong><em>iTunes user? Just tap <a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/inside-the-hive-with-nick-bilton/id1232383877?mt=2\">here</a> to listen to</em> Inside the Hive <em>at your convenience. And don’t forget to subscribe.</em></strong></p>\n<p>Of all the hot takes that have come from the administration and/or the people in its orbit&#8212;<a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2017/08/trump-charlottesville-on-many-sides-white-supremacy\">Nazis are fine</a>! Furloughs are <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/white-house-to-furloughed-workers-consider-it-a-free-vacation\">vacations</a>! <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/09/trump-death-toll-puerto-rico-democrat-hoax\">Nobody died in Puerto Rico</a>! <a href=\"https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2019/02/trump-north-korea-economic-rocket-kim-jong-un.html\"><strong>Kim Jong Un</strong> rocks</a>!&#8212;this obviously ranks very high in the Hall of Fame. <em>The U.S. kidnaps, murders, and dismembers U.S. residents all the time! We shouldn’t judge a country for chopping someone up if that’s what’s considered normal there! M.B.S. is just a young dictator trying to make his mark on the world!</em> To be fair, Barrack’s comments are no worse than Trump’s actions but the president is <a href=\"http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2018/01/trump-is-mentally-unwell-and-everyone-around-him-knows-it.html\">mentally impaired</a> and shouldn’t be looked to as some sort of moral guide.</p>\n<p>Unsurprisingly, at some point, it got back to Barrack&#8212;who has <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/13/world/middleeast/trump-tom-barrack-saudi.html\">extensive ties to Saudi Arabia</a>&#8212;that his comments weren’t going over very well. As of Wednesday afternoon, he’d issued a sort-of apology:</p>\n<div class=\"embed block row social-twitter\"><blockquote class=\"embed twitter-embed-component twitter-tweet twitter-tweet\" lang=\"en\" data-type=\"twitter\" data-url=\"https://twitter.com/maggieNYT/status/1095768112090222592\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/maggieNYT/status/1095768112090222592\">https://twitter.com/maggieNYT/status/1095768112090222592</a></p></blockquote></div><p>Luckily, at this point, coming off like a stooge of an authoritarian regime is probably the least of Barrack’s problems. In December, prosecutors <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/13/us/politics/trump-inauguration-investigation.html\">launched</a> a criminal probe into the spending of Trump’s inauguration committee, which Barrack oversaw. Specifically, they’re investigating whether foreign donors from the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, and Saudi Arabia illegally funneled donations to the committee in order to influence U.S. policy, which of course is a thing this administration would never, ever stand for. (Barrack is cooperating with the inquiry.)</p>\n<p><em><strong>If you would like to receive the Levin Report in your inbox daily, <a href=\"http://tinyletter.com/besslevin\">click here</a> to subscribe.</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Nobody cares more about the working class than Trump</strong></p>\n<div class=\"embed block row social-twitter\"><blockquote class=\"embed twitter-embed-component twitter-tweet twitter-tweet\" lang=\"en\" data-type=\"twitter\" data-url=\"https://twitter.com/frankthorp/status/1095758576461713409\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/frankthorp/status/1095758576461713409\">https://twitter.com/frankthorp/status/1095758576461713409</a></p></blockquote></div><p>As a reminder, the reason federal contractors&#8212;among them, janitors and cafeteria workers&#8212;missed more than a month of pay was <em>because</em> of Trump.</p>\n<p><strong>Report: lawyer in charge of Apple‘s insider-trading policy could do better in some areas</strong></p>\n<p>“<a href=\"https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-13/ex-top-apple-lawyer-levoff-accused-by-sec-of-insider-trading\">Everything looks good here but next year let’s have you work on not insider trading Apple stock</a>.”</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><strong>Gene Daniel Levoff,</strong> who until last year was Apple’s senior director of corporate law, repeatedly traded on non-public revenue-and-earnings filings dating back to 2011, the Securities and Exchange Commission and federal prosecutors said Wednesday. The illegal investments led to about $227,000 in profits, while allowing him to avoid $377,000 of losses, according to the U.S. attorney’s office in Newark, New Jersey, which filed criminal charges against Levoff.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>For instance, in July 2015, Levoff learned that Apple wouldn’t meet analysts’ third-quarter forecast for iPhone sales, the S.E.C. said in a related civil complaint. That month, he sold about $10 million of Apple stock&#8212;virtually all of his holdings. When the company reported earnings, its shares plunged more than 4 percent. Levoff avoided losing about $345,000, the S.E.C. said.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Kevin Marino,</strong> Levoff’s attorney, told Bloomberg he is reviewing the charges and looks forward to defending his client “with respect to these allegations.”</p>\n<p><strong>Lonely group of millionaires wants higher taxes</strong></p>\n<p>If you ask the super-rich decrying recent tax proposals as the <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/davos-billionaires-aoc-tax-proposal\">first in a series of steps</a> that <a href=\"https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2019/01/29/bloomberg-compares-warren-ultra-millionaire-tax-venezuela/HjIQ22sfeOl4OZyDTNetBN/story.html\">end in the collapse of Western society</a>, these people should be locked in a tower and never heard from again. <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/12/business/rich-people-against-tax-cut.html\">Per <em>The New York Times</em></a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><strong>Stephen Prince,</strong> a Democrat from Nashville, is none too pleased about his windfall. He believes the Trump tax cuts are misguided and ultimately bad for the country, even as they pad his already robust bank account. “I’m pissed off about it,” said Mr. Prince, speaking via FaceTime during a four-month, around-the-world cruise with his wife.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Mr. Prince has found camaraderie among an ad hoc group of wealthy individuals known as the Patriotic Millionaires. Founded in 2010 by <strong>Morris Pearl,</strong> a former BlackRock executive, the loose-knit group advocates higher taxes on businesses and the wealthy. In recent years, they have met with legislators in Washington and various state capitals, testified before Congress and endorsed candidates who endorse higher taxes on the rich.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>“We’re very concerned about this huge inequality thing,” Pearl told the <em>Times.</em> “And the tax cut was designed to make the rich richer. I don’t work at all, but I’m making more money than most people who do work, and I’m paying less taxes than they do. It’s a pretty good deal if you can get it, but it’s not good for the country.”</p>\n<p><strong>Jack Dorsey loves what Elon Musk is doing on Twitter</strong></p>\n<p>Which is: courting defamation lawsuits and getting sued by the S.E.C., <a href=\"https://www.marketwatch.com/story/jack-dorsey-says-elon-musk-is-his-favorite-twitter-user-misses-the-irony-2019-02-12\">among other things</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Twitter Inc. Chief Executive Jack Dorsey raised some eyebrows Tuesday during a chaotic live-tweet interview when he was asked who’s the most exciting and influential person on his platform. . . . While Musk is among the most prolific and newsworthy tweeters in Silicon Valley, that has also been to his detriment. Musk has been accused of bullying journalists on Twitter, and Tesla stock has regularly swung wildly based on Musk’s candid tweets, leading some analysts and investors to suggest he should rein in his tweeting habit.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Some of his tweets have had serious consequences: Musk is facing a defamation lawsuit for calling a British cave diver a pedophile in a tweet, and he lost his job as chairman of Tesla last year as part of a settlement with the Securities and Exchange Commission after an ill-fated tweet that suggested Tesla had financial backing to go private&#8212;in fact, it did not, leading to allegations that he misled investors.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Elsewhere!</strong></p>\n<p>U.S. Tax Revenues Fall, Deficit Widens in Wake of New Tax Law (<a href=\"https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-tax-revenue-declined-0-4-in-2018-11550084426?\"><em>W.S.J.</em></a>)</p>\n<p>Bank of America says no going back on its $400m plans for Brexit move (<a href=\"https://www.ft.com/content/b9d43bba-2f7a-11e9-8744-e7016697f225\"><em>Financial Times</em></a>)</p>\n<p>How a Nasdaq Loophole Fueled One Stock’s Rise of 3,750 Percent (<a href=\"https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-a-nasdaq-loophole-fueled-one-stocks-rise-of-3-750-11550066400\"><em>W.S.J.</em></a>)</p>\n<p><strong>Neri Oxman</strong> Has Pershing Square Capital Up Almost 25 Percent on the Year (<a href=\"https://dealbreaker.com/2019/02/bill-ackman-up-big-on-love\">DealBreaker</a>)</p>\n<p>Royalties on 1983 Finance Classic “Trading Places” Go Up for Bid (<a href=\"https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-12/royalties-on-1983-finance-classic-trading-places-go-up-for-bid\">Bloomberg</a>)</p>\n<p>Fed official warns against inadvertently crimping U.S. growth (<a href=\"https://www.ft.com/content/91bd0a4c-2fb8-11e9-8744-e7016697f225\"><em>Financial Times</em></a>)</p>\n<p>Zinke teaming up with Lewandowski at D.C. lobbying firm (<a href=\"https://www.politico.com/story/2019/02/13/ryan-zinke-lobbying-firm-1168926\">Politico</a>)</p>\n<p>Chuck E. Cheese’s denies conspiracy theory that it reuses pizza slices (<a href=\"https://nypost.com/2019/02/12/chuck-e-cheese-denies-conspiracy-theory-that-it-reuses-pizza-slices/\"><em>N.Y.P.</em></a>)</p>","rubric":"Levin Report","socialTitle":"Trump Backer Sorry for Saying We Shouldn’t Judge Saudi Arabia for Murder by Bone Saw","socialDescription":"Tom Barrack apologized for “not making it clear” that he considers the murder of Jamal Khashoggi “reprehensible.”","seoTitle":"Trump Backer Sorry for Saying We Shouldn’t Judge Saudi Arabia for Murder by Bone Saw","seoDescription":"Tom Barrack apologized for “not making it clear” that he considers the murder of Jamal Khashoggi “reprehensible.”","channel":"News","subChannel":"Business","issueDate":"","ledeCaption":"“What I meant to say was...”","contentSource":"web","canonicalUrl":"","interactiveOverride":"","contentType":"","textMimeType":"","tags":["tom barrack","donald trump","Mohammed bin Salman","saudi arabia","Jamal Khashoggi"],"revisionAuthor":"Jarondakie Patrick","meta":{"collectionName":"articles","modelName":"article","publishable":true,"identifiable":true,"image":false,"archived":false,"hallable":true,"hierarchical":false},"id":"5c6493e0003afa5aebada28a","revision":11,"createdAt":"February 13, 2019 5:02 pm","modifiedAt":"February 13, 2019 6:31 pm","revisionCreatedAt":"February 13, 2019 6:31 pm","_embedded":{"categories-channels":[{"fields":{"name":"Business","slug":"business","revisionAuthor":"aviator-scripts-categories-migration","meta":{"collectionName":"categories","modelName":"category","publishable":false,"identifiable":false,"image":false,"archived":false,"hallable":false,"hierarchical":true},"id":"5ae9f120c639a3587939aa6f","revision":0,"createdAt":"May 2, 2018 1:10 pm","modifiedAt":"May 2, 2018 1:10 pm","revisionCreatedAt":"May 2, 2018 1:10 pm","modelName":"category","collection":"categories","contributors":{},"photos":{},"hierarchy":[],"parent":[],"root":[]}}],"categories-tags":[{"fields":{"name":"tom barrack","slug":"tom-barrack","revisionAuthor"