ns to combat obesity. (One regulation attempted to ban large sodas more than 16 ounces, one of the many policies that led people to accuse him of turning the city into a nanny state.) During the 2008 economic crisis, he argued that he needed to have a third term to guide the finance-dependent city through the years of turbulence ahead. His exacting management style turned post-9/11 New York City, a town left for broke decades earlier, into essentially one of the world’s greatest businesses, a gleaming metropolis with plummeting crime rates, skyrocketing wealth, renewed real-estate development, and an ominous undercurrent of gentrification, the targeting of minority men with stop-and-frisk, and widening income inequality.</p>\n<p>Bloomberg has always been well meaning, even if his measures appear out of touch with reality: after he settled into a post-mayoral career of anti-gun activism and philanthropy, he had the urge to go back into public life, considering a run for president when the unpopular <strong>Donald Trump</strong> and <strong>Hillary Clinton</strong> seemed to be the two candidates headed for the general election. But his trial balloon never quite took off. “I love our country too much to play a role in electing a candidate who would weaken our unity and darken our future&#8212;and so I will not enter the race for president of the United States,” he wrote on Bloomberg View, the opinion section of Bloomberg News, probably the most apt outlet in which he could have made the announcement.</p>","socialMedia":[],"photos":{"tout":[{"aspectRatios":{"3:2":{"width":1050,"height":700,"modifications":{"crop":{"x":103,"height":700,"width":1050}}},"5:3":{"width":1165,"height":699,"modifications":{"crop":{"x":117,"width":1165,"height":699}}},"2:3":{"width":466,"height":699,"modifications":{"crop":{"x":467,"width":466,"height":699}}},"16:9":{"width":1232,"height":693,"modifications":{"crop":{"x":84,"width":1232,"height":693}}},"4:3":{"width":932,"height":699,"modifica