nist: Stop “Demeaning” Billionaires by Calling Them Billionaires","dek":"Isn’t criticizing the rich just anti-billionaire discrimination?","promoDek":"Isn’t criticizing the rich just anti-billionaire discrimination?","body":"<p>The past few weeks have been extremely tough on billionaires. Democratic lawmakers have <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/davos-billionaires-aoc-tax-proposal\">proposed</a> tax plans that could take them from “insanely, mind-bogglingly rich” to simply “absurdly rich.” One of their brethren announced he was seriously considering running for president in 2020, and instead of throwing him a parade and saying, “Thank god you got here when you did!”, people <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/mike-bloomberg-howard-schultz-2020\">told him</a> he was making a horrible mistake. A single individual was <a href=\"https://thehill.com/policy/finance/427674-historian-accuses-billionaires-at-davos-of-not-paying-their-fair-share-in\">mean to them at Davos</a>. Not one of them was invited to the State of the Union to highlight the epidemic of billionaire bullying. Obviously, this isn’t the sort of treatment billionaires signed up for when they entered the “fuck-ton of money” tax bracket, the contract for which specifically states they are to be exclusively praised and lionized for their wealth&#8212;a covenant that has been been violated in the most perverse of ways of late.  Luckily, a few brave souls&#8212;a kind of Freedom Riders, but for billionaires&#8212;are finally standing up and saying, enough. <em>The oppression must end.</em></p>\n<p>At Bloomberg, owned by billionaire <strong>Mike Bloomberg,</strong> columnist <strong>Tyler Cowen</strong> <a href=\"https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-02-07/stop-demeaning-billionaires-such-as-howard-schultz\">believes</a> we should stop demeaning billionaires by calling them billionaires, because in doing so we are “objectifying” them. It’s rude, he argued, to “casually describe individuals by their net wealth,” which is “often a preliminary step toward making others seem less human or less deserving of respect.” He went on:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I would hesitate, for example, before referring to someone publicly as “in the $150,000 range of net wealth,” even if most people knew that to be true. If I were a real-estate broker, I might talk about a customer this way, but it would be in a private context with another broker. Even then, calling someone “my $350,000 customer” or some such isn’t something that would endear me to Miss Manners.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>You might feel it is different when a person’s net wealth is very high, such as when the word “billionaire” is deployed. But that distinction does not sit easy with me. If we use the word “billionaire” for this reason, then aren’t we also sending a negative message about the non-billionaires? At any rate, the people mocking <strong>[Howard] Schultz</strong> the most do not seem to be trying to give the word “billionaire” positive connotations.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Of course, one of the reasons people have been using the term “billionaire” derisively when describing the Starbucks C.E.O. is because they have an issue with the fact that the only reason he’d be able to get into the 2020 race (and likely give us <a href=\"https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-07/schultz-s-independent-bid-in-2020-would-help-trump-poll-finds\">another four years of <strong>Donald Trump</strong></a>) is because of his vast wealth. Another, perhaps, is that Schultz has come out against proposals like that of Rep. <strong>Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez,</strong> with such declarations as, “I don’t think we want a 70 percent income tax in America.” That Schultz should be demonized for this, <a href=\"https://www.wsj.com/articles/whos-afraid-of-howard-schultz-11548893911\">argues</a> <em>The Wall Street Journal</em>’s editorial board, is tantamount to treason:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Democrats might benefit from re-acquainting themselves with the private economy and wealth creation, which is damaged by punitive taxation. Mr. Schultz could point this out in debates and note how the success of Starbucks allowed him to provide thousands of Americans with jobs, good health care, and the $30 million to help veterans navigate the workforce that Mr. Schultz has written about in these pages.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Elsewhere in recent pleas to stop being so mean to the rich, <em>The Wall Street Journal</em>’s <strong>Jason L. Riley,</strong> enraged that billionaire <strong>Ken Griffin’s</strong> purchase of the most expensive home in U.S. history received news coverage, bravely declared that “<a href=\"https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-a-billionaire-spends-his-money-is-his-own-business-11548807054\">how a billionaire spends his money is his own business</a>.” (In what we’re sure was an innocent omission, the article did not mention the <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/hedge-funds-got-bailout-bucks-too-2009-3\">$200 million</a> Griffin’s hedge fund received in taxpayer bailout funds during the financial crisis.) Meanwhile, the <em>Journal</em> also thinks it‘s the height of unfair that, if we’re going to allow “identity politics” to play a part in the next presidential election, one can “<a href=\"https://www.wsj.com/articles/democrats-love-diversity-except-when-it-comes-to-thought-11549411119\">identify as black</a>” but not as a <a href=\"https://www.wsj.com/articles/grande-vs-keurig-billionaires-11548978810\">billionaire</a>, because it’s become such a dirty word.</p>\n<p>And yet, there may be hope. Perhaps, if the moniker is reclaimed to denote “genius, altruist, better than everyone else on earth,” things could change. It’ll take a lot of work&#8212;marches, demonstrations, brave souls who aren’t afraid to speak up&#8212;but it’ll be worth it, to tell our children we didn’t stand in silence.</p>\n<h3>More Great Stories from <em>Vanity Fair</em></