,"root":[],"slug":"billionaires"}]},"contributors":{"author":[{"id":"582375aeaf70ea5e7082bcd1","modelName":"contributor","collection":"contributors","bio":"","email":"","name":"Bess Levin","socialMedia":[]}]},"inlineEmbeds":[],"photos":{"tout":[{"revisionAuthor":"Kevin Fitzpatrick","filename":"howard-schultz-starbucks-2020.jpg","aspectRatios":{"3:2":{"width":1998,"height":1332,"override":false,"modifications":{"crop":{"height":1332,"width":1998,"x":1,"y":0}},"duration":null},"5:3":{"width":2000,"height":1200,"override":false,"modifications":{"crop":{"height":1200,"width":2000,"x":0,"y":0}},"duration":null},"2:3":{"width":887,"height":1331,"override":false,"modifications":{"crop":{"x":130,"y":1,"height":1331,"width":887}},"duration":null},"9:16":{"width":746,"height":1327,"override":false,"modifications":{"crop":{"x":201,"y":5,"height":1327,"width":746}},"duration":null},"7:3":{"width":1994,"height":854,"override":false,"modifications":{"crop":{"x":2,"y":14,"height":854,"width":1994}},"duration":null},"16:9":{"width":2000,"height":1125,"override":false,"modifications":{"crop":{"x":0,"y":4,"height":1125,"width":2000}},"duration":null},"4:3":{"width":1239,"height":929,"override":false,"modifications":{"crop":{"x":0,"y":1,"height":929,"width":1239}},"duration":null},"1:1":{"width":912,"height":912,"override":false,"modifications":{"crop":{"x":120,"y":0,"height":912,"width":912}},"duration":null},"master":{"format":"JPEG","url":"https://cn-copilot-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/vf/production/2019/01/27/5c4dd6d8cec32271820c6e79_howard-schultz-starbucks-2020.jpg","width":2000,"height":1333,"duration":null}},"title":"howard-schultz-starbucks-2020.jpg","credit":"Stephen Brashear/Getty Images","cropMode":"TOP","meta":{"collectionName":"photos","modelName":"photo","publishable":false,"identifiable":false,"image":true,"archived":false,"hallable":false,"hierarchical":false},"restrictCropping":false,"id":"5c4dd6d9cec32271820c6e7a","revision":1,"createdAt":"January 27, 2019 11:05 am","modifiedAt":"January 27, 2019 11:07 am","revisionCreatedAt":"January 27, 2019 11:07 am","altText":"Howard Schultz speaking at the Starbucks annual meeting of shareholders in Seattle, Washington.","description":"","tags":["howard schulz"],"modelName":"photo","collection":"photos"}]},"pubDate":"February 7, 2019 2:23 pm","related":[],"template":"default","url":"/news/2019/02/stop-demeaning-billionaires-by-calling-them-billionaires","videos":{}},{"hed":"Inside the Bloomberg Vanity Fair Climate Exchange","promoHed":"Inside the Bloomberg Vanity Fair Climate Exchange","dek":"Luminaries gathered at Bloomberg HQ&#8212;the most sustainable building in the world&#8212;to celebrate those who are working to divert climate change catastrophe.","promoDek":"Luminaries gathered at Bloomberg HQ&#8212;the most sustainable building in the world&#8212;to celebrate those who are working to divert climate change catastrophe.","body":"<p>When <strong>Sir Norman Foster</strong> was commissioned to design Bloomberg’s European headquarters, he was charged with balancing two ambitious objectives: aesthetic brilliance and environmental innovation. True to form, the multi-award-winning architect behind the Gherkin, the Millennium Bridge and the vast glass dome that frosts Germany’s Reichstag surpassed expectations. Rising above a restored Roman temple on a 3.2-acre site between Bank and St Paul’s, the 10-storey building was awarded the 2018 Royal Institute of British Architects (RIBA) Prize. Fitted with bronze lung-like blades that work as natural ventilators, smart airflow controls, and a water conservation system that saves 25 million litres of water each year (enough to fill 10 Olympic swimming pools), it has also been named the most sustainable office in the world. “It has not just raised the bar for office design and city planning, but smashed the ceiling,” said RIBA president, <strong>Ben Derbyshire</strong>, when describing the “once-in-a-generation project”.</p>\n<p>With its ceiling-smashing credentials, Bloomberg HQ was the natural space to host the inaugural Bloomberg <em>Vanity Fair</em> Climate Exchange, which took place on December 11 and 12, 2018, closing a febrile year of environmental advance, tumult, hope and despair. In October, the UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change released a landmark report warning that we have just 12 years to avert catastrophe by working to limit global warming to a maximum of 1.5°C. A mere half-degree rise beyond this level, they wrote, will significantly aggravate the risk of droughts, floods, extreme temperatures and acute poverty for large swathes of the world’s population. The report was commissioned at the United Nations Climate Change Conference in Marrakech in 2016. Since then, the chasm between politics and environmental science has deepened. Leading the charge, <strong>Donald Trump</strong> has withdrawn from the Paris Agreement, and cast climate change research as a partisan, anti-business ill. Similarly, Brazil’s new president <strong>Jair Bolsonaro</strong> has dismissed environmental protections, and removed Brazil from the list of potential hosts for the UN’s upcoming climate conference.</p>\n<p>As some lawmakers negate their responsibility to safeguard the environment, and others remain too divided to conceive and implement pioneering legislation, the Exchange was an opportunity to gather a network of leading figures, outline the shared, systemic problems threatening every industry, and also offer a panoramic insight into the work of the groups and individuals who are enacting change.</p>\n<p>The opening of the Exchange was marked with a glittering Gala dinner. Arriving outside Bloomberg HQ (thought to be the largest stone building built in the City of London since St Paul’s Cathedral), guests were confronted with Danish-Icelandic artist <strong>Olafur Eliasson</strong>’s installation, Ice Watch. Six enormous hulks of blue-hued, slowly melting hunks of glacial ice extracted from the waters surrounding Greenland, the sculptures were intended to serve as a visual reminder of the impact of climate change. Moving inside, and into a line of futuristic transparent lifts, guests arrived at the office’s large atrium area, which is dominated by a bronze ramp called the Vortex that spans six desk-filled floors, winding towards a glazed rooflight.</p>\n<p>As the crowd swelled to include <strong>Tracey Emin</strong>, <strong>Rod Stewart</strong>, <strong>Tom Daley</strong>, <strong>Gizzi Erskine</strong>, <strong>Yana Peel</strong> and <strong>Paloma Faith</strong>, the model, activist and actress <strong>Lily Cole</strong>&#8212;wearing a <strong>Christopher Raeburn</strong> two-piece fashioned from 1950s Royal Air Force silk maps&#8212;took a break from the drinks reception and made her way to <em>Vanity Fair</em>’s signature portrait studio, where photographer <strong>Matt Holyoak</strong> was busily shooting guests spanning politics, business, fashion and the arts. She was soon followed by a stream of stars, including <em>Crazy Rich Asians</em> actress <strong>Victoria Loke</strong>, actor <strong>Rob Lowe</strong>, and <strong>Stella McCartney</strong>, whose date for the evening was model <strong>Arizona Muse</strong>. Sitting down for dinner at two long, flower-laden tables, guests were soon treated to  a surprise appearance from <strong>Ellie Goulding</strong> who, after belting out a roster of hits, sat for her own portrait.</p>\n<p>The following day was introduced by <em>Vanity Fair</em> editor <strong>Radhika Jones</strong> and <strong>Michael R. Bloomberg</strong>, who was appointed UN Special Envoy for Cities and Climate Change in 2014, and has consistently advocated for the US to move towards clean energy. Primarily operating through Bloomberg Philanthropies, he has invested millions of dollars into sustainability, often working at a municipal level to avoid becoming embroiled in America’s choked federal system.</p>\n<p>The first act focused on business and culture, and was opened by London Mayor <strong>Sadiq Khan</strong>, whose theme was the relation between cities and climate-friendly business. “In the absence of national leadership, it’s cities, business and civil society that can and must step into the breach to ensure we honour the Paris Agreement,” said Khan, echoing comments that Bloomberg himself made when speaking to <em>Vanity Fair</em> in December: “Cities are where people are, and they’re where the carbon emissions are. So if you get cities to do the right thing, you can make an awful lot of progress.”</p>\n<p>Next up was a conversation between <strong>Christiane Amanpour</strong>, CNN’s chief international anchor, and designer Stella McCartney, exploring the ways that the fashion industry can help curb climate change. A champion of sustainable practices long before they became trendy (the fashion industry contributes 10 per cent of global greenhouse emissions), McCartney even sourced animal-friendly shoes in her Central Saint Martins graduate fashion show (these were overshadowed by the fact they were modelled by her friends <strong>Kate Moss</strong> and <strong>Naomi Campbell</strong>). Later, setting up her eponymous label after a successful stint at Chloé, McCartney set herself ambitious sustainability targets and advocated animal welfare, ultimately stirring a movement that has since swelled and inspired other luxury brands to follow suit: Gucci, Armani, Versace and Burberry have all shunned fur. “Because the fashion industry has a significant impact on the environment, there is an enormous opportunity for consequential change,” McCartney explained to Amanpour, stressing the business case for sustainable fashion, and expanding on the recent UN fashion industry charter for climate action. “Ultimately, it’s the smart decision for the planet and for our industry.”</p>\n<p>After performances from a selection of spoken-word poets, the curtain lifted on the second act: oceans. Moderated by <strong>Ian Urbina</strong>, the investigative reporter for <em>The New York Times</em>, who has reported on Pulitzer Prize-winning stories and whose articles are regularly adapted into films, the panel talk focused on the positive impact of conserving coral and protecting oceans from overfishing. <strong>Baroness Patricia Scotland QC</strong>, secretary-general of the Commonwealth, dialled in via video link to join <strong>Tony Long</strong>, CEO of Global Fishing Watch, and chairman <strong>Anisa Kamadoli Costa</strong>, who spearheads Tiffany &amp; Co’s sustainability efforts. These began in earnest when the iconic jewellery maker made the unprecedented move of removing coral&#8212;often called the nursery of the oceans&#8212;from their products. “We have a real responsibility&#8212;and opportunity&#8212;to set the trend for what sustainable luxury means in the jewellery industry,” said Kamadoli Costa, who holds the dual title of president of the Tiffany &amp; Co Foundation and chief sustainability officer, in an interview with VF before the Exchange. “Sustainable luxury is quality and craftsmanship, but also the environmental and social standards that we choose to uphold. We have the power and privilege of using the Tiffany brand to make an impact. I don’t think now is the time to stay silent.”</p>\n<p>The third act was energy, and saw <strong>Mayor William Peduto</strong> of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania&#8212;the “Paris of Appalachia”&#8212;discuss the challenges of transitioning off coal and its impacts on public health, and the urgency of local leadership in the fight against climate change. “Cities and citizens have an important role to play in the fight against climate change,” said Mayor Peduto, who expressed his frustration at Trump’s decision to withdraw from the Paris Agreement in the documentary Paris to Pittsburgh, which looks at the city’s efforts to reduce carbon emissions. “I was proud to represent my city at the COP [United Nations Conference of Parties] in Poland and again here in London as we continue to find ways to unite the various actors in this critical time.”</p>\n<p>Coinciding with the third anniversary of the signing of the Paris Agreement, the Exchange aimed to galvanise progress ahead of the upcoming UN Climate Change Summit, which promises to be a fraught, urgent affair. But the focus wasn’t just negative. The Exchange also celebrated the progress being made across multiple spheres, spotlighting the creativity and entrepreneurial acuity being channelled towards safeguarding the natural world, restructuring the cities we live in and empowering individuals to enact change. “Climate change has proven to be both a short- and long-term threat with this year demonstrating some of the worst impacts on citizens worldwide,” said Michael R. Bloomberg. “Following on from world leaders gathering in Poland to discuss the issue, the Climate Exchange has highlighted the human impact and solutions.”</p>","rubric":"From the Magazine","socialTitle":"Inside the Bloomberg Vanity Fair Climate Exchange","socialDescription":"Luminaries gathered at Bloomberg HQ—the most sustainable building in the world—to celebrate those who are working to divert climate change catastrophe.","seoTitle":"Inside the Bloomberg Vanity Fair Climate Exchange","seoDescription":"Luminaries gathered at Bloomberg HQ—the most sustainable building in the world—to celebrate those who are working to divert climate change catastrophe.","channel":"AList","subChannel":"Culture","issueDate":"Hollywood 2019","ledeCaption":"","contentSource":"magazine","canonicalUrl":"","interactiveOverride":"","contentType":"","textMimeType":"","tags":[],"revisionAuthor":"Charlotte Sutherland-Hawes","meta":{"collectionName":"articles","modelName":"article","publishable":true,"identifiable":true,"image":false,"archived":false,"hallable":true,"hierarchical":false},"id":"5c62ae31003afa5aebada1bb","revision":13,"createdAt":"February 12, 2019 6:29 am","modifiedAt":"February 12, 201