billionaire, having “already begun the groundwork required to be on the ballot in all 50 states” as an independent. (Schultz will reportedly spend the next three months traveling the country&#8212;perhaps, say, to Iowa&#8212;before making an official announcement.) Unsurprisingly, the news raised the hackles of fellow billionaire <strong>Donald Trump,</strong> who took time out of his busy day of <a href=\"https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1089883338758914048\">attacking</a> the <a href=\"https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1089691564283183105\">media</a> and <a href=\"https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1089876055224184833\">arguing against the separation of church and state</a> to claim that Schultz has neither the brains nor the balls to run for office:</p>\n<div class=\"embed block row social-twitter\"><blockquote class=\"embed twitter-embed-component twitter-tweet twitter-tweet\" lang=\"en\" data-type=\"twitter\" data-url=\"https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1089881244312178688\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1089881244312178688\">https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1089881244312178688</a></p></blockquote></div><p>But Trump wasn’t the only member of the three-comma club to come out against Schultz’s (kind-of) candidacy. On Monday afternoon, <strong>Mike Bloomberg</strong> issued a statement on his Web site saying that <a href=\"https://www.mikebloomberg.com/news/mike-bloomberg-statement-independent-run/\">the notion of running as an independent is a horrible idea</a>, and one that will almost certainly put Trump back in the White House for a second term. “I have never been a partisan guy,” the former New York City mayor wrote, “and it’s no secret that I looked at an independent bid in the past. In fact, I faced exactly the same decision now facing others who are considering it. The data was very clear and very consistent. Given the strong pull of partisanship and the realities of the electoral college system, there is no way an independent can win. That is truer today than ever before. In 2020, the great likelihood is that an independent would just split the anti-Trump vote and end up re-electing the president. That’s a risk I refused to run in 2016 and we can’t afford to run it now.”</p>\n<p>To some, the idea of Bloomberg warning Schultz off an independent bid is the height of rich, even if he’s clearly 100 percent right. But as the <a href=\"https://www.forbes.com/profile/michael-bloomberg/#59bf86d61417\">$48 Billion Dollar Man</a> himself points out, he’s been studying up on how to lose elections for <em>years,</em> and after considering independent runs in 2008, 2012, and 2016, he has the data to say definitively it should never be attempted, particularly when it raises the chances of giving an unhinged lunatic another four years in the White House. That’s not to say Bloomberg has an issue with putting another, richer billionaire in office through the two-party system:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>With an estimated net worth of $3.3 billion, Mr. Schultz, 65, is one of several billionaires who had been mentioned as possible presidential contenders. The former hedge-fund titan <strong>Tom Steyer,</strong> who had been eyeing a run, announced this month he would focus his energies on a private effort to impeach Mr. Trump. And Mr. Bloomberg has also been contemplating a presidential run.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That’s a prospect that has Wall Street licking its lips, even if financiers know, deep down inside, that the idea of President Bloomberg is little more than an extremely niche fantasy. “I’m a socially liberal, fiscally conservative centrist who would love to vote for a rational Democrat and get Trump out of the White House,” an anonymous C.E.O. of one of the nation’s largest banks <a href=\"https://www.politico.com/story/2019/01/28/wall-street-2020-economy-taxes-1118065\">told</a> Politico’s <strong>Ben White.</strong> “Personally, I’d love to see Bloomberg run and get the nomination. I’ve just never thought he could get the nomination the way the primary process works.”</p>\n<p><em><strong>If you would like to receive the Levin Report in your inbox daily, <a href=\"http://tinyletter.com/besslevin\">click here</a> to subscribe.</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Schultz’s listening-tour is off to a great start</strong></p>\n<div class=\"embed block row social-twitter\"><blockquote class=\"embed twitter-embed-component twitter-tweet twitter-tweet\" lang=\"en\" data-type=\"twitter\" data-url=\"https://twitter.com/alexis_levinson/status/1090039389495939072\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/alexis_levinson/status/1090039389495939072\">https://twitter.com/alexis_levinson/status/1090039389495939072</a></p></blockquote></div><p><strong>Speaking of Wall Street’s hopes and fears for 2020</strong></p>\n<p>It should surprise virtually no one to hear that two words <a href=\"https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-warren-eyes-white-house-big-banks-brace-for-browbeating-11548671401\">are keeping the industry up at night</a>: <strong>Elizabeth Warren:</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Warren’s presidential bid will be driven by her populist assault on big banks that helped her rise to prominence during the financial crisis and in her successful 2012 Massachusetts Senate race.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Although the economy has recovered and new, stricter regulations remain largely in place, Ms. Warren sees cause for further vigilance, and many on Wall Street dread another round of criticism on an even bigger national stage&#8212;the Democratic presidential primary race.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>“She has this sort of applause line that we are all crooks, which is scary that you may hear that for a year and a half,” said a large U.S. bank executive who asked to remain anonymous for fear of a Warren backlash.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Still, at least some on Wall Street understand that a president who might nominate regulators who actually hold the industry accountable or insist on stricter oversight of the people that brought you <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2017/10/elizabeth-warren-eviscerates-equifax-for-profiting-off-screw-up\">the Equifax hack</a>, is <a href=\"https://www.politico.com/story/2019/01/28/wall-street-2020-economy-taxes-1118065\">preferable</a> to an unpredictable lunatic who drags the country into self-defeating trade wars and shuts the government down because someone forgot to feed him his Big Macs and his blood sugar plummeted.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Among the most hardcore Democrats on Wall Street, the strong desire is to find a candidate&#8212;any candidate&#8212;who can beat Trump, even if that means getting behind someone like Warren who supports policies that bankers hate.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>“Everybody just wants to win,” a senior executive told Politico. “It’s as wide open as I’ve ever seen it. There is no gravitational force that everyone is sort of running towards. Everyone has their candidate. Frankly, if people believed Warren would win, they’d jump on board. And everyone in the top tier not named Bernie Sanders could probably win.”</p>\n<p><strong>Wall Street’s #MeToo takeaway: avoid women women like the plague</strong></p>\n<p>“I now think twice about spending one-on-one time with a young female colleague,” a U.S. finance executive <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/27/world/europe/metoo-backlash-gender-equality-davos-men.html\">confessed</a> to <em>The New York Times</em> on the sidelines of the World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland, requesting anonymity because the issue is “just too sensitive.” Apparently worried they might accidentally sexually harass someone, “a number of men have [said] that they will avoid going to dinner with a female mentee,” and that they’re “concerned about deploying a woman solo on-site with a male,” <strong>Pat Milligan,</strong> who advises multi-national companies on gender and diversity issues, told reporter <strong>Katrin Bennhold.</strong> Men who don’t know how to behave around women in a way that couldn’t be construed as harassment: the true victims of #MeToo!</p>\n<p><strong>A.O.C. puts big tech on notice</strong></p>\n<p>In a letter co-signed by Representative <strong>Chellie Pingree,</strong> the freshman congresswoman told Facebook, Microsoft, and Google that she was “deeply disappointed” to learn that the companies “were high-level sponsors of a conference this month . . . known as LibertyCon, that included a session denying established science on climate change.” Noting that the corporations have pledged to reduce their carbon footprints and committed to pursuing renewable energy, the lawmakers said that such efforts were undercut by “implicit support of the session organized at LibertyCon.” Likening today’s “coordinated campaign to deny climate change, or to put a positive spin on its effects” as “not unlike that of the tobacco companies which once sought to discredit their product’s link to cancer,” Ocasio-Cortez and Pingree said the tech giants must ensure that such climate-change propaganda “do not reflect the values of your companies going forward,“ whether intentional or otherwise.</p>\n<p><strong>What Trump’s shutdown hath wrought</strong></p>\n<p>A day after president and his chief of staff <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/trump-is-already-threatening-a-second-shutdown\">threatened</a> to shut down the government for a second time come February 15, the Congressional Budget Office <a href=\"https://www.politico.com/story/2019/01/28/government-shutdown-cost-1123735\">reported</a> that the 35-day temper tantrum cost the U.S. economy roughly $3 billion in lost economic activity that “will not be recouped.” Meanwhile, federal contractors, who will not receive back pay for five weeks of lost wages, will have to wait another month until receiving a full paycheck, because their companies will have to wait to be paid by the government. (“It feels like we are still hostages,” <strong>Janice Morgan,</strong> who also had her insurance cut off during the shutdown, <a href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/it-feels-like-we-are-still-hostages-federal-contractors-who-lost-health-insurance-during-shutdown-remain-in-limbo/2019/01/27/9a1020a2-20c3-11e9-9145-3f74070bbdb9_story.html\">told</a> <em>The Washington Post.</em>) And how ‘bout <a href=\"https://www.desertsun.com/story/news/environment/2019/01/26/joshua-tree-national-park-rally-against-shutdown-impact/2689866002/\">those national parks</a>?</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The federal government shutdown may be over, but fans of Joshua Tree National Park are still angry and upset about the furlough that kept park rangers off the job. . . . Park gates remained open during the shutdown as vandals cut down several Joshua trees and damaged rocks. Without park maintenance crews for the first three weeks, volunteers stepped up to clean bathrooms and collect trash. <strong>Curt Sauer,</strong> who retired as Joshua Tree National Park superintendent in 2010, praised the work of volunteers and lamented the damage caused to the park from illegal campfires, camping and vehicle travel. “What’s happened to our park in the last 34 days is irreparable for the next 200 to 300 years,” he said.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Remember Gary Cohn asked C.E.O.s to raise their hands if they were going to spend their tax-cut savings on investments no one did?</strong></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.nbcnews.com/business/economy/1-5-trillion-tax-cut-had-no-major-impact-business-n963411\">Turns out they weren’t kidding</a>!</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The Trump administration’s $1.5 trillion tax cut package appeared to have no major impact on businesses’ capital investment or hiring plans, according to a survey released a year after the biggest overhaul of the tax code in more than 30 years.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The National Association of Business Economics’ quarterly business conditions poll, published on Monday, found that while some companies reported accelerating investments because of lower corporate taxes, 84 percent of respondents said they had not changed plans. That compares to 81 percent in the previous survey published in October.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>“A large majority of respondents, 84 percent, indicate that one year after its passage, the corporate tax reform has not caused their firms to change hiring or investment plans,” said NABE president <strong>Kevin Swift.</strong> As a reminder, the White House’s big argument for the tax bill was that it would lead to an investment boom, with companies showering workers with their billions in tax savings.</p>\n<p><strong>Elsewhere!</strong></p>\n<p>Treasury Set to Borrow $1 Trillion for a Second Year to Finance the Deficit (<a href=\"https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-28/another-year-another-1-trillion-in-new-debt-for-u-s-to-raise\">Bloomberg</a>)</p>\n<p>Bridgewater, RenTech Make $13 Billion in a Grim Year for Hedge Funds (<a href=\"https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-28/bridgewater-rentech-make-13-billion-in-a-grim-hedge-fund-year\">Bloomberg</a>)</p>\n<p>“Another frustration with manufacturing in Texas: American workers won’t work around the clock. Chinese factories have shifts working at all hours, if necessary, and workers are sometimes even roused from their sleep to meet production goals. That was not an option in Texas.” (<a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/28/technology/iphones-apple-china-made.html\"><em>N.Y.T.</em></a>)</p>\n<p>U.S. sanctions Venezuela state-owned oil firm in bid to transfer control to Maduro opposition (<a href=\"https://www.cnbc.com/2019/01/28/treasury-set-to-sanction-venezuela-state-owned-oil-firm-sen-rubio.html\">CNBC</a>)</p>\n<p>U.S. Lifts Sanctions on Russian Oligarch’s Companies (<a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/27/us/politics/trump-russia-sanctions-deripaska.html\"><em>N.Y.T.</em></a>)</p>\