/2019/02/michael-jackson-broadway-musical-allegations-leaving-neverland\">in 2020</a>&#8212;decried  <em>Leaving Neverland</em> in January. “This is yet another lurid production in an outrageous and pathetic attempt to exploit and cash in on Michael Jackson,” the family wrote in a <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/michael-jackson-documentary-leaving-neverland-surviving-r-kelly\">statement</a>. The estate used even harsher words to describe the film in a <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/michael-jackson-estate-calls-neverland-doc-tabloid-character-assassination\">later statement</a>, calling the project “the kind of tabloid character assassination Michael Jackson endured in life, and now in death.” Jackson, who died in 2009, did face accusations of abuse when he was alive as well: the musician was indicted on charges including four counts of molesting a minor in 2004. In 2005, a jury found him not guilty on all charges. Jackson was also accused of sexually abusing a 13-year-old boy in 1993, and settled out of court with the boy’s family for more than $20 million in 1994.</p>\n<p>According to <a href=\"https://deadline.com/2019/02/leaving-neverland-trailer-michael-jackson-hbo-documentary-dan-reed-1202560263/\">Deadline</a>, HBO said last week that it had no plans to meet with representatives from Jackson estate, which has continued to <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/02/michael-jackson-estate-leaving-neverland-letter-channel-4\">push back</a> against the film with claims the filmmakers never approached Jackson’s estate, or any of his family, friends, or defenders while assembling their documentary. “Those concerned should be given an appropriate and timely opportunity to respond,” a letter from the estate’s representative reportedly read. “I think we can all agree that the false allegations being made in your ‘documentary’ are ‘significant allegations’ . . . it is hard to imagine more significant accusations that can possibly be made against anyone.”</p>\n<p>Responding to the controversy surrounding the doc at the T.C.A.s, Deadline reports that HBO’s <strong>Casey Bloys</strong> said, “The one thing I would say about this documentary is I would ask everybody to watch it and make their judgments after seeing it.”</p>\n<h3>More Great Stories from <em>Vanity Fair</em></h3>\n<p>&#8212; The <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/02/the-worst-kept-secret-of-trumps-presidency?inline\">worst-kept secret</a> of Trump’s presidency</p>\n<p>&#8212; Is Silicon Valley suffocating the media? <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/how-google-and-facebook-are-strangling-their-digital-offspring?inline\">Jill Abramson weighs in</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; Bernie Sanders’s <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/01/bernie-sanders-estate-tax-billionaires?inline\">plan to eat the rich</a></p>\n<p>&#8212; The 25 <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/25-best-movie-scenes?inline\">most influential movie scenes</a> of the past 25 years</p>\n<p>&#8212; <em>Broad City</em> and the <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/01/broad-city-millennial-rage-ilana-glazer-abbi-jacobson?inline\">pivot to millennial rage</a></p>\n<p>Looking for more? <a href=\"https://www.vanityfair.com/newsletters\">Sign up</a> for our daily Hollywood newsletter and never miss a story.</p>","rubric":"coming soon","socialTitle":"Leaving Neverland Trailer Dives Deep on Dark Memories of Michael Jackson","socialDescription":"The two-part documentary, which premieres on HBO March 3, is going to be a very tough watch.","seoTitle":"Leaving Neverland Trailer Dives Deep on Dark Memories of Michael Jackson","seoDescription":"The two-part documentary, which premieres on HBO March 3, is going to be a very tough watch.","channel":"Hollywood","subChannel":"Television","issueDate":"","ledeCaption":"","contentSource":"web","canonicalUrl":"","interactiveOverride":"","contentType":"","textMimeTy